{"title_page": "Australian Egg Corporation Limited", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Australian Egg Corporation\n| logo = \n| type = [[Agricultural corporation]]\n| genre = \n| foundation = 2002\n| founder = \n| location_city = [[Sydney]]\n| location_country = [[Australia]]\n| location = 107 Mount Street, North Sydney\n| origins = \n| key_people = \n| area_served = \n| industry = \n| products = \n| services =\n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = \n| divisions =\n| subsid = \n| owner = \n| company_slogan = \n| homepage =\n| dissolved = \n| footnotes = \n}}\nThe '''Australian Egg Corporation Limited''' ('''AECL''') is the major marketer of [[egg (food)|eggs]] in Australia.  It is a producer-owned corporation, representing approximately 400 commercial egg producers and is based in [[Sydney]]. The activities of  AECL include [[marketing]], [[research and development]], and policy services.  According to its website, it runs public awareness campaigns on [[animal welfare]], [[nutrition]], and [[vaccine]] development.<ref>[https://www.australianeggs.org.au/ Australian Egg Corporation Limited Website]</ref> However, it has received criticism from animal welfare organisations for using these terms for promotional purposes.<ref>[http://www.animalsaustralia.org/take_action/forgotten-battery-hens Hens abandoned in mega factory farm]</ref> The corporation is affiliated with the [[International Egg Commission]] (IEC).\n\nThe AECL was created by an act of [[Parliament of Australia|federal parliament]] in 2002 as a [[statutory authority]] to replace the [[Rural Industries Research and Development Corporation]], as the peak egg body in the country.\n\nIn September 2004, the corporation hosted the Annual Conference of the IEC in Sydney. It was awarded the International body's most prestigious prize, the Golden Egg Award. At the same presentation night, the Australian egg industry was judged as the best in the world by an international judging panel.{{Citation needed|date=January 2008}}\n\nIn July 2005, the corporation funded a trip for Brian Spotts of Colorado, to break the world record of standing eggs on end. {{Citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\nIn 2013, consumer rights organisation [[Choice (Australian consumer organisation)|Choice]] made a super-complaint against the AECL after it proposed to change the definition for [[free range eggs]] in Australia from 2000 hens per hectare to 10000 hens per hectare.<ref>[http://www.choice.com.au/media-and-news/media-releases/2013-media-releases/choice-makes-free-range-super-complaint.aspx CHOICE makes free-range super-complaint]</ref> In 2014, the AECL was fined $30000 for faking an egg shortage during an oversupply to boost their profits.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/environment/animals/egg-producers-sought-to-cull-chickens-and-destroy-eggs-in-bid-to-raise-prices-accc-20140528-393uv.html Egg producers sought to cull chickens and destroy eggs in bid to raise prices: ACCC]</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.aecl.org/ Australian Egg Corporation Limited]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040929045434/http://www.aph.gov.au/Library/pubs/bd/2002-03/03bd041.htm Parliamentary Library : Establishment of the Corporation]\n*[http://www.internationalegg.com International Egg Commission]\n*[http://www.9news.com/acm_news.aspx?OSGNAME=KUSA&IKOBJECTID=d21a2c19-0abe-421a-0119-752de9a31f28&TEMPLATEID=0c76dce6-ac1f-02d8-0047-c589c01ca7bf Article regarding world-record winner for balancing eggs, a venture funded by the AECL]{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Agriculture companies of Australia]]\n[[Category:Government-owned companies of Australia]]\n[[Category:Poultry farming in Australia]]\n[[Category:Egg organizations]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Australian Egg Corporation\n| logo = \n| type = [[Agricultural corporation]]\n| genre = \n| foundation = 2002\n| founder = \n| location_city = [[Sydney]]\n| location_country = [[Australia]]\n| location = 107 Mount Street, North Sydney\n| origins = \n| key_people = \n| area_served = \n| industry = \n| products = \n| services =\n| revenue = \n| operating_income = \n| net_income = \n| num_employees = \n| parent = \n| divisions =\n| subsid = \n| owner = \n| company_slogan = \n| homepage =\n| dissolved = \n| footnotes = \n}}\nThe '''Australian Egg Corporation Limited''' ('''AECL''') is the major marketer of [[egg (food)|eggs]] in Australia.  It is a producer-owned corporation, representing approximately 400 commercial egg producers and is based in [[Sydney]]. The activities of  AECL include [[marketing]], [[research and development]], and policy services.  According to its website, it runs public awareness campaigns on [[animal welfare]], [[nutrition]], and [[vaccine]] development.<ref>[https://www.australianeggs.org.au/ Australian Egg Corporation Limited Website]</ref> However, it has received criticism from animal welfare organisations for using these terms for promotional purposes.<ref>[http://www.animalsaustralia.org/take_action/forgotten-battery-hens Hens abandoned in mega factory farm]</ref> The corporation is affiliated with the [[International Egg Commission]] (IEC).\n\nThe AECL was created by an act of [[Parliament of Australia|federal parliament]] in 2002 as a [[statute|statutory]] [[authority]] to replace the [[Rural Industries Research and Development Corporation]], as the peak egg body in the country.\n\nIn September 2004, the corporation hosted the Annual Conference of the IEC in Sydney. It was awarded the International body's most prestigious prize, the Golden Egg Award. At the same presentation night, the Australian egg industry was judged as the best in the world by an international judging panel.{{Citation needed|date=January 2008}}\n\nIn July 2005, the corporation funded a trip for Brian Spotts of Colorado, to break the world record of standing eggs on end. {{Citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\nIn 2013, consumer rights organisation [[Choice (Australian consumer organisation)|Choice]] made a super-complaint against the AECL after it proposed to change the definition for [[free range eggs]] in Australia from 2000 hens per hectare to 10000 hens per hectare.<ref>[http://www.choice.com.au/media-and-news/media-releases/2013-media-releases/choice-makes-free-range-super-complaint.aspx CHOICE makes free-range super-complaint]</ref> In 2014, the AECL was fined $30000 for faking an egg shortage during an oversupply to boost their profits.<ref>[http://www.smh.com.au/environment/animals/egg-producers-sought-to-cull-chickens-and-destroy-eggs-in-bid-to-raise-prices-accc-20140528-393uv.html Egg producers sought to cull chickens and destroy eggs in bid to raise prices: ACCC]</ref>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.aecl.org/ Australian Egg Corporation Limited]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040929045434/http://www.aph.gov.au/Library/pubs/bd/2002-03/03bd041.htm Parliamentary Library : Establishment of the Corporation]\n*[http://www.internationalegg.com International Egg Commission]\n*[http://www.9news.com/acm_news.aspx?OSGNAME=KUSA&IKOBJECTID=d21a2c19-0abe-421a-0119-752de9a31f28&TEMPLATEID=0c76dce6-ac1f-02d8-0047-c589c01ca7bf Article regarding world-record winner for balancing eggs, a venture funded by the AECL]{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Agriculture companies of Australia]]\n[[Category:Government-owned companies of Australia]]\n[[Category:Poultry farming in Australia]]\n[[Category:Egg organizations]]\n", "name_user": "Daask", "label": "safe", "comment": "linkstatutory authorityusingFind link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Australian_Egg_Corporation_Limited"}
{"title_page": "Kitana", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Infobox character\n| color              = #0800FF\n| name               = Kitana\n| image              = File:KitanaMK11.png\n| image_size         = 250px\n| caption            = Kitana in ''[[Mortal Kombat 11]]'' (2019)\n| series             = [[Mortal Kombat]]\n| first              = ''[[Mortal Kombat II]]'' (1993)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.ign.com/characters/kitana |title=Kitana |publisher=Uk.ign.com |date= |accessdate=2013-11-01}}</ref>\n| creator            = [[John Tobias]]\n| designer           = John Tobias (''MKII'', ''UMK3''/''MKT'')<br>Mark Lappin (''MK:SM'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=46532&tab=credits |title=Mortal Kombat: Shaolin Monks - Credits |publisher=Allgame.com |date=2010-10-03 |accessdate=2013-11-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141116021746/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=46532&tab=credits |archivedate=2014-11-16 |df= }}</ref><br>Cy Mandua (''MKvDCU'')<br>Atomhawk Design (''MK2011'')<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.atomhawk.com/characters.html |title=Characters |publisher=Atomhawk.com |date= |accessdate=2013-11-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131103054125/http://www.atomhawk.com/characters.html |archive-date=2013-11-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| portrayer          = [[Katalin Zamiar]] (''MKII'')<br />Becky Gable (''UMK3'', ''MKT'')<br />Kaprice Imperial (''MK11'')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.Instagram.com/p/BwpJE_UFFrP/ |title=Instagram |publisher=@mpmanagementchicago | accessdate=2019-04-29}}</ref>\n| motion_actor       = Lorrisa Julianus (''MKvDCU'')<ref>{{cite web |url=http://geodepress.com/continued-interview-with-lorrisa-julianus-aka-zenobia/ |title=Geode Press LLC - Continued Interview with Lorrisa Julianus AKA Zenobia |publisher=Geodepress.com |date=2013-01-08 |accessdate=2015-05-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402094109/http://geodepress.com/continued-interview-with-lorrisa-julianus-aka-zenobia/ |archivedate=2015-04-02 |df= }}</ref><br />Brenda Barrie (''MK2011'')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BwpJE_UFFrP/ |title=MP Management Chicago |publisher=Instagram.com |date= |accessdate=2019-04-29}}</ref><br />Emily Marso (''MK11'')<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BwmexrQhhnZ/ |title=Instagram |publisher=@missmarso |date=2019-04-23 |accessdate=2019-04-24}}</ref>\n| voice              = Rosalind Dugas (''MK4'')<br />Lita Lopez (''MK:SM'')<br />S.G. Willie (''MKvDCU'')<br />[[Karen Strassman]] (''MK2011'', ''MKX'')<ref name=va>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindthevoiceactors.com/characters/Mortal-Kombat/Kitana/ |title=Characters - Voice Of Kitana |publisher=Behindthevoiceactors.com |date= |accessdate=2013-11-01}}</ref><br />[[Kari Wahlgren]] (''MK11'')<br />[[Grey DeLisle|Grey Griffin]] (''MKX'' (In grunt voice)<ref>https://twitter.com/GreyDeLisle/status/590327143076208640?s=19</ref>,''MKL:SR'')\n| origin             = Edenia\n| family             = Jerrod (father; deceased)<br>[[Sindel]] (mother)<br>[[Shao Kahn]] (stepfather)<br>[[Mileena]] (half-sister)\n| weapon             = [[Tessenjutsu|Steel Fans]] (all media except the first film) <br />Flying Blade (''MKG'')<br />[[Glaive]]/[[B\u014d|Bo Staff]] (''MKX'') <br />Sais (''MK11'')\n| lbl21              = Fighting styles\n| data21             = [[Eagle Claw]] (''MK:DA'', ''MK:U'')<br />[[Baguazhang|Ba Gua]] (''MK:DA'', ''MK:U'', ''MK:A'')<br>\n}}\n\n'''Kitana Kahn''' or ('''Lady Kitana''') is a [[fictional character]] from the ''[[Mortal Kombat]]'' media franchise. She was introduced as one of the new [[player character]]s in the [[fighting game]] ''[[Mortal Kombat II]]'' in 1993. Since then, Kitana appeared in a majority of ''Mortal Kombat'' series' video games and its other media, including the films ''[[Mortal Kombat (1995 film)|Mortal Kombat]]'' and ''[[Mortal Kombat: Annihilation]]'', and the series ''[[Mortal Kombat: Defenders of the Realm]]'', ''[[Mortal Kombat: Konquest]]'', and ''[[Mortal Kombat: Legacy]]'', becoming one of the most popular and recognizable characters of the franchise.\n\nOne of the lead characters of the ''Mortal Kombat'' saga, Kitana is the princess of Outworld and the adopted daughter of the emperor, [[Shao Khan]]. She has a \u201ctwin\u201d sister [[Mileena]] and personal bodyguard and best friend [[Jade (Mortal Kombat)|Jade]] always at her side. Through the course of events in the series, she learns that she is actually the daughter of Queen [[Sindel]] and King Jerrod, the rulers of Edenia, a realm that was conquered and destroyed by Shao Khan. She discovers that Mileena is not actually her sister, but a clone created by the emperor\u2019s sorcerer [[Shang Tsung]] intended to watch over and spy on her. Kitana rebels and sides with the Earthrealm warriors to fight against Shao Khan and ultimately free her realm from being a part of Outworld.\n\nKitana has received positive critical reception for her role in the franchise, evolving from one of the three female ninja [[palette swap]]s to one of the main protagonists of the series.\n\n==Appearances==\n===In video games===\nKitana first appears in ''[[Mortal Kombat II]]'' (1993) as a member of the Edenian race in the fictional other dimension called Outworld. She is over ten thousand years old, although she appears to be a young woman.<ref name=\"OldschoolMK\">{{cite web|url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/features/top-10-old-school-mortal-kombat-characters/2 |title=Top 10 Old School Mortal Kombat Characters: Page 2 |publisher=Game Revolution |date= |accessdate=2012-01-10}}</ref> For most of her life, Kitana believed she was the daughter of Shao Kahn and Queen Sindel. She served as Shao Kahn's personal elite assassin for centuries, working alongside her sister Mileena and her best friend Jade.<ref name=\"MKwarehouseMKII\">{{cite web|url=http://mortalkombatwarehouse.com/mk2/kitana/ |title=Mortal Kombat II: Kitana |publisher=Mortal Kombat Warehouse |date= |accessdate=2012-01-10}}</ref> Eventually, she found out the truth: Shao Kahn murdered her true father King Jerrod, usurped his throne, and claimed Sindel as his wife to maintain rule. He placed Kitana under a spell to be his loyal daughter and assassin, and had his subordinate [[Shang Tsung]] create a disfigured clone of her to be a backup heir.<ref name=\"MKwarehouseMKII\"/> That clone, Mileena, would spy on Kitana and kill and replace her if she ever rose against Shao Kahn. Realizing her life had been a lie, she turned against Shao Kahn and began fighting alongside Earthrealm's champions to defeat the evil emperor and free her home realm of his tyranny.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamerant.com/mortal-kombat-series-summary-mortal-kombat-2-cj-79888/all/1/ |title=A History of Violence: A Look Back At The Mortal Kombat Series (Part 1) |author=C.J. Smillie |publisher=Game Rant |date=April 18, 2011 |accessdate=2012-01-10}}</ref> At this point, Kitana started developing romantic interest in Earthrealm champion [[Liu Kang]]. She also came to hate Mileena for being a reminder of the lie and existing only to kill her.{{#tag:ref|In Kitana's ladder mode uncanonical ending of the 2011 reboot game, however, she takes pity on Mileena, sparing and accepting her \"royal blood\" after Shao Kahn is defeated, and the two sisters (and Jade) team-up to fight against the forces of evil.<ref>Jon Michael and Ryan Scott, [http://uk.ps3.gamespy.com/playstation-3/mortal-kombat-x/guide/page_20.html Mortal Kombat - ps3 - Walkthrough and Guide - Page 20], GameSpy, January 19, 2011.</ref> This stood out as an abrupt departure from their usual relations so far in the original timeline, in which Kitana refuses to accept Mileena's demand to co-rule during their shared ending of ''Mortal Kombat Gold'' (resulting in Mileena's imprisonment in Kitana's canonical version of this confrontation).|group=\"note\"}} According to the semi-canonical spin-off game ''[[Mortal Kombat: Shaolin Monks]]'' (2005), after Kitana was found no longer loyal to Kahn, she is put into a spell-induced trance and forced to fight the Earthrealm heroes (along with Mileena and Jade), before being freed from this state by the [[Shaolin in popular culture|Shaolin warrior monks]] Liu Kang and [[Kung Lao]]. Eventually, the sisters clash and Kitana slays Mileena.\n\nDuring the events of ''[[Mortal Kombat 3]]'' (1995), Kitana is put on trial for treason after killing Mileena.<ref name=\"MKwarehouseUMK3\">{{cite web|url=http://mortalkombatwarehouse.com/umk3/kitana/ |title=Ultimate Mortal Kombat 3: Kitana |publisher=Mortal Kombat Warehouse |date= |accessdate=2012-01-10}}</ref>{{#tag:ref|According to the later canon, as neither Kitana nor Mileena are actually mentioned in the original version of ''Mortal Kombat 3'' at all. In a non-canonical short story prequel to ''MK3'' published in Poland by [[CD Projekt]], Kitana is instead beaten and killed by [[Sonya Blade]] while still serving Shao Kahn.|group=\"note\"}} Before a verdict and sentence could be reached, however, Kitana escapes (as [[retcon]]ned in ''MK3'' update releases ''[[Ultimate Mortal Kombat 3]]'' and ''[[Mortal Kombat Trilogy]]'') and joins the warriors of Earthrealm to free her mother Sindel, who has been resurrected and used by Kahn to invade Earth. After convincing her close friend Jade to join her, Kitana locates and frees Sindel from Shao Kahn's mental control,<ref name=\"MKwarehouseUMK3\"/> leading to his defeat at the hands of Liu Kang. Kitana, Sindel, and Jade then liberate Edenia from Outworld.\n\nTheir jubilation is short-lived, as during ''[[Mortal Kombat Gold]]'' (1999), [[Shinnok]] and his grand vizier [[Quan Chi]] escapes imprisonment in the Netherrealm and invades Edenia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mortalkombatwarehouse.com/mkg/kitana/ |title=Mortal Kombat Gold: Kitana |publisher=Mortal Kombat Warehouse |date= |accessdate=2012-01-10}}</ref> Betrayed by the traitorous Edenian [[Tanya (Mortal Kombat)|Tanya]], Kitana, Sindel, and Jade are taken prisoner, but Kitana manages to escape<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamerant.com/mortal-kombat-series-summary-4-special-forces-cj-80309/all/1/ |title=A History of Violence: A Look Back At The Mortal Kombat Series (Part 3) |author=C.J. Smillie |publisher=Game Rant |date=April 20, 2011 |accessdate=2012-01-10}}</ref> and rejoin her Earthrealm allies. Shinnok's forces are eventually defeated by the joint efforts of Kitana and her allies. With Edenia freed once again, Kitana proposes to Liu Kang, offering him the chance to rule Edenia at her side as King and Queen, but he reluctantly rejects her offer, seeing his true duty as champion of Earth. After Shinnok's defeat, Kitana captures Mileena but learns that Shao Kahn has survived his defeat in Earthrealm and is regaining power. Knowing that Kahn would attempt to reclaim Edenia once he was strong enough, she forges an alliance with [[Goro (Mortal Kombat)|Goro]], prince of the Outworld race Shokan, against Kahn's forces.\n\nIn ''[[Mortal Kombat: Deadly Alliance]] (2002)'', Kitana, leading a preemptive strike against Shao Kahn's forces,<ref>''Mortal Kombat Deadly Alliance'' GameCube manual, page 22.</ref> learns that he has been slain by unknown assassins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mortalkombatwarehouse.com/mkda/kitana/ |title=Mortal Kombat: Deadly Alliance: Kitana |publisher=Mortal Kombat Warehouse |date= |accessdate=2012-01-10}}</ref> Thinking her fight is at an end, she begins the journey back to Edenia, hoping to finally live in peace. However, on the way she encounters Kung Lao, who tells her of the plans of the Deadly Alliance of Quan Chi and Shang Tsung, who are responsible for Liu Kang and Shao Kahn's demise and are attempting to revive the undead army of the legendary Onaga the Dragon King. Despite Kitana's grief, she rejoins the Earthrealm warriors and leads them into battle. During the assault on Shang Tsung's palace, she faces Quan Chi one-on-one but despite her improved fighting skills, gained from training with [[Bo' Rai Cho]], Kitana is outmatched and killed alongside her allies. Shortly after, they are resurrected and magically enslaved by Onaga,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mortalkombatwarehouse.com/mkd/kitana/ |title=Mortal Kombat: Deception: Kitana |publisher=Mortal Kombat Warehouse |date= |accessdate=2012-01-10}}</ref> who then sends Mileena to impersonate Kitana as the princess of Edenia.\n\nIn ''[[Mortal Kombat: Deception]]'' (2004), Onaga uses Kitana to defeat and imprison her mother, Sindel, knowing that the princess would not fight her mother. Sindel is freed from her own dungeon by Jade, and together they flee to Outworld where they attempt to find a way to defeat Onaga and free Kitana from his influence. Unknown to anyone at the time, Liu Kang's spirit was able to remain amongst the living due to the bond he shared with Kitana.<ref name=\"MKAbio\">[https://web.archive.org/web/20090116044523/http://mkarmageddon.com/assets/bios/bio_nightwolf.html Nightwolf's bio] at the official ''Mortal Kombat Armageddon'' website. Retrieved on 2007-01-23.</ref> He found himself a new ally and friend in [[Ermac]], as the two embark on a mission to save their allies as well. Ermac and Liu Kang are successful in freeing Kitana and the other Earthrealm heroes.\n\nAfterward, as Kitana travels back to Edenia, she encounters [[Blaze (Mortal Kombat)|Blaze]], who warns her of a coming new danger that will threaten all the realms and advises her to assemble the forces of light into battle. Weary of constant battle, Kitana is disheartened, but Blaze assures her that the wars will soon be over. Following this warning, Kitana returns in ''[[Mortal Kombat: Armageddon]]'' (2006), accompanied by Liu Kang's spirit in order to keep him whole until there was a way to reunite him with his body. They later meet with [[Nightwolf]], who offers to relieve Kitana of her burden to take Liu Kang's soul into himself, allowing her to fight against the coming evil. Kitana ultimately perishes with the rest of her allies during the battle.\n\nIn the uncanonical crossover game ''[[Mortal Kombat vs. DC Universe]]'' (2008), Kitana is transported to [[Metropolis (comics)|Metropolis]], where she encounters her counterpart from the [[DC Universe]], [[Wonder Woman]]. Due to the \"kombat rage\", Kitana hallucinates, believing Wonder Woman to be an assassin sent from Outworld and challenged her. After being defeated, Kitana flees to elsewhere in Metropolis, where she is found and defeated by [[Scorpion (Mortal Kombat)|Scorpion]] and brought to [[Raiden (Mortal Kombat)|Raiden]]'s temple, where she tells about seeing the fusion of Shao Kahn and [[Darkseid]]: [[Dark Kahn]]. Kitana then joins the rest of the Kombatants in traveling to the fused realms of Outworld and [[Apokolips]]. She fights alongside them against the DC heroes and villains, and is one of the many knocked unconscious while Raiden and [[Superman]] battle and destroy Dark Kahn.\n\nKitana re-appears in [[Mortal Kombat (2011 video game)|''Mortal Kombat'']], the 2011 re-imagining of the first three ''Mortal Kombat'' games.<ref>Randy Nelson, [http://www.joystiq.com/2010/08/18/mortal-kombats-latest-kombatants-cyrax-and-kitana/ \"Mortal Kombat's latest kombatants: Cyrax and Kitana\"], Joystiq, August 18th 2010.</ref> In the game's story mode, she and Jade are sent by Shao Kahn to compete in Mortal Kombat. Kitana battles Liu Kang in an attempt to ensure that he will not reach the final stages of the first tournament, but is defeated; expecting to die, she is surprised by his decision to spare her. Later, during the second tournament, Kitana is approached by Raiden, who informs her that her supposed past as Shao Kahn's daughter is a lie. Plagued bu doubts, she infiltrates Shang Tsung's flesh pits and discovers the newly-created Mileena. Before Kahn, she accuses Shang Tsung of attempting to replace her, and is shocked to learn that the Emperor himself ordered Mileena's creation. He then imprisons Kitana in the palace, prior to execution, and commands his \"true daughter\" to be brought to him. Kitana is soon freed by Liu Kang, and she and Jade escape to Earthrealm to join their new allies against the forces of Outworld. They assist in the battle for Earthrealm, but are killed alongside several others by Kitana's corrupted mother, Sindel. In the end, she is shown to be one of the warriors that are resurrected by Quan Chi in the Netherrealm to battle Raiden.\n\nIn both timelines, Kitana is killed and becomes some form of a revenant - one timeline she serves Onaga and is freed by the spirit of Liu Kang, while in the other timeline she serves Quan Chi until Raiden dethrones Shinnok, and Quan Chi is killed by Hanzo Hasashi (Scorpion), leaving the Netherealm to be ruled by both her and the revenant Liu Kang.\n\nKitana returns in ''[[Mortal Kombat X]]'' (2015).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.cheatcc.com/395954|title=New Mortal Kombat X Trailer Shows Off Kitana - Cheat Code Central|publisher=News.cheatcc.com|accessdate=17 January 2015}}</ref> In the story mode she is one of Quan Chi's revenants. She fights [[Jax (Mortal Kombat)|Jax]] and [[Cassie Cage]] in the game's story mode, and after Quan Chi's death and Shinnok's defeat, she and fellow revenant Liu Kang become the new rulers of the Netherrealm.\n\nKitana returns in ''[[Mortal Kombat 11]]'' (2019), as both her revenant and her still-living past self. Immediately after Kung Lao defeated Quan Chi and Shang Tsung in the second tournament, Kronika's time anomaly brought Kitana and most of her allies and enemies into the future. She and Jade remain in Outworld with Kotal Kahn to find and defeat the time-displaced Shao Kahn, while Raiden, Kung Lao and Liu Kang return to Earthrealm to learn more about their future selves, as well as the events that transpired in this timeline. To aid Kotal, Kitana attempts to forge an alliance with Sheeva and her Shokan army, but Sheeva will not commit unless the Tarkatans also join. After learning a news from Kung Lao and Liu Kang of Jade and Kotal\u2019s capture by Shao Kahn, Kitana and her Shaolin allied rescue Jade, and at the same time make peace with the time-displaced Baraka and his Tarkatans, who join her ranks. Later, Kitana and her new army rescue Kotal from being executed, with the princess defeating and blinded Shao Kahn personally, rendered the tyrant powerless without his sight. Kotal, now crippled from his battle with Shao Kahn, steps down as the Kahn of Outworld, appoints Kitana as a new worthy Kahn, due to her greater charisma for uniting all of Outworld's denizens with respect than Kotal ever was. After Liu Kang is kidnapped by Kronika, Kitana and her Outworld army aid Earthrealm's allied force of Special Forces and Shaolin against Kronika's army, until Raiden merges with both iterations of Liu Kang into Fire God Liu Kang. As the rest of her allies fight off Kronika's remaining army, Kitana and Kung Lao manage to reach Kronika's Time Keep with Liu Kang. However, Kitana and her allies are affected by Kronika's time-reverse, leaving Liu Kang to fight Kronika and Cetrion alone. In one of the game's endings, the true ending, Kitana becomes Liu Kang's partner to forge a new timeline. Before reshaping the universe with Liu Kang, Kitana tells him that whatever they do, evil will rise someday, and that mortals will still make choices they cannot foresee. Liu Kang replies that each realm must choose its own destiny, and that whatever happens, they will face those events together.\n\n====Design history and derived characters====\n[[File:Kitana Tobias.jpg|thumb|left|A comparison of [[John Tobias]]' sketch of the unused character \"Kitsune\" in then original ''[[Mortal Kombat (1992 video game)|Mortal Kombat]]'' (1992) and his concept art for Kitana in ''[[Ultimate Mortal Kombat 3]]'']]\n\nIn 2009, Kitana's origins were revealed by her creator, [[John Tobias]], who disclosed that she started out as an unplayable [[herald]]-type character called \"Kitsune\" during the early development of the original ''[[Mortal Kombat (1992 video game)|Mortal Kombat]]'' game in 1991; his inspiration at the time was the character of Princess Mariko from [[Jordan Mechner]]'s 1984 video game ''[[Karateka (video game)|Karateka]]''.{{#tag:ref|Jordan Mechner commented: \"Ha thanks, that's awesome! Kitsune/Kitana vs Mariko... not sure who I'd bet on!\"<ref>[https://twitter.com/jmechner/status/111287084081352704 Jordan Mechner: @therealsaibot] on Twitter.</ref>|group=\"note\"}} In Tobias' design sketch, Kitsune wielded a single ornamental fan and \"was going to fit into the story as Shang Lao's [early Shang Tsung] princess daughter\u2014the spoil of victory for winning the tournament\" who would betray her father after she fell for Scorpion. Shang instead became a minion of Shao Kahn when the story was expanded for ''Mortal Kombat II'', for which Kitsune was renamed \"Kitana\" and made Kahn's stepdaughter keeping up with the princess character idea.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.retrozap.com/argcast-mini-14-making-mortal-kombat-with-john-tobias/|title=ARGcast Mini #14: Making Mortal Kombat with John Tobias|last=ARGpodcast|date=2018-06-26|website=RetroZap|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref> According to Tobias, her original name was rejected for being Japanese and thus not compatible with \"Shang and Shao who were both Chinese in origin\" (before the games \"ultimately became a hodgepodge of nonsensical [[List of Asian mythologies|Asian mythological]] hooha anyway\"), and the name Kitana was created as \"a combo of [[Kitsune]] & [[Katana]]\" that would sound \"generically Asian enough.\"<ref>[https://twitter.com/therealsaibot John Tobias (therealsaibot) on Twitter] (a series of posts on September 7, 2011).</ref> By replacing [[Sonya Blade]] with the masked Kitana in the first sequel, the developers could easily add multiple female playable characters through [[palette swapping]], as they had previously done in the first game with the male ninjas.\n\n''Mortal Kombat'' co-creator and producer [[Ed Boon]] said Kitana's iconic \"Kiss of Death\" (or \"Kiss of Doom\") [[Fatality (Mortal Kombat)|Fatality]] was inspired by the demise of the villain Mr. Big (Dr. Kananga) in the 1973 [[James Bond]] film ''[[Live and Let Die (film)|Live and Let Die]]'', adding that it was his favorite finishing move of ''MKII'' and one of the best examples of their attempt to combine violent and humorous elements in the game.<ref>{{cite video game|title=Mortal Kombat: Armageddon Premium Edition |developer=Midway |publisher=Midway |date=October 11, 2006 |level=\"The History of Fatalities\" commentary}}</ref> Her ''Ultimate Mortal Kombat 3'' / ''Trilogy'' [[Fatality (Mortal Kombat)#Animality|Animality]] transformation animal is a small killer rabbit in a homage to ''[[Monty Python and the Holy Grail]]'',<ref name=\"ossm\" /> and her non-canonical ending in the ''Mortal Kombat 2011'', in which she forms an alliance with Jade and Mileena, is a reference to ''[[Charlie's Angels]]''.<ref>{{cite tweet|number=474558501088284672|user=noobde|title=RT @liamx2000 I hope @noobde &amp; his team don't cut out Kitana , Mileena &amp; Jade.. my faves. EB: Good Morning Angels!|author=Ed Boon|date=5 June 2014}}</ref> Besides the \"Kiss of Death\", Kitana's other most commonly recurring Fatality is an execution through [[decapitation]] with a bladed fan, which has been featured in almost all of her game appearances (except of ''Mortal Kombat: Deadly Alliance'' and ''Mortal Kombat vs. DC Universe'') and is expanded in ''Mortal Kombat 2011'' where she cuts off the defeated opponents' arms before beheading them. During the early 1990s, there has been a popular yet completely false rumor regarding the supposed Nudality (or Sexuality), a unique finishing move to use either by or against Kitana and Mileena.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamingtarget.com/article.php?artid=5593|title=April Fool's Day Scams|last=Scalza|first=John|date=2003-04-01|publisher=Gaming Target|accessdate=2010-10-23}}</ref>\n\nBoon described Kitana and Mileena as the female equivalents of Scorpion and [[Sub-Zero (Mortal Kombat)|Sub-Zero]], the series' two most iconic male characters with a fierce rivalry of their own.<ref name=\"kk\">[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eFu7OyFjc6M Kitana's Kombat Kard video] for ''Mortal Kombat: Deception''.</ref> Speaking in 2009, Boon said Kitana had become of the most recognizable ''Mortal Kombat'' characters, alongside Scorpion, Sub-Zero, and the series' official protagonist Liu Kang.<ref>{{cite web|first=Gary |last=Walk |title=Interview: Ed Boon on The Ups and Downs of the Mortal Kombat Franchise |date=2008-11-17 |url=http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/features/interview-ed-boon-on-the-ups-and-downs-of-the-mortal-kombat-franchise/?biz=1&page=1 |publisher=GameDaily |accessdate=2009-09-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090505220824/http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/features/interview-ed-boon-on-the-ups-and-downs-of-the-mortal-kombat-franchise/?biz=1&page=1 |archivedate=May 5, 2009 }}</ref> Prior to the release of ''Mortal Kombat X'', the game's lead designer John Edwards said Kitana had remained his favorite character.<ref>{{cite web|last=Gerardi |first=Matt |url=https://www.avclub.com/article/mortal-kombat-xs-lead-designer-mulls-dedicated-sum-205760 |title=Mortal Kombat X's lead designer mulls a dedicated \"summon Kitana\" button \u00b7 The Gameological Questionnaire\u00b7 The A.V. Club |publisher=Avclub.com |date= |accessdate=2014-06-22}}</ref><ref>Jason Wilson, Adam Hernandez, ''Mortal Kombat: Prima Official Game Guide'', Prima Games 2011 (p. 7).</ref>\n\nKitana was originally portrayed by [[karate]] and [[taekwondo]] practitioner [[Katalin Zamiar]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Katalin Rodriguez Ogren |url=http://www.chicagonow.com/pow-mixed-martial-arts/2010/10/i-am-the-original-kitana-and-no-it-wont-be-my-halloween-costume/#image/1 |title=I am the Original Kitana and No, It Won\u2019t Be My Halloween Costume &#124; POW! Mixed Martial Arts & Fitness |publisher=Chicagonow.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-20}}</ref> She was hired for the role after Boon and Tobias, who have been members of her fitness center,<ref name=\"ppa\" /> were contacted by her brother, a ''Mortal Kombat'' fan who proposed that she would take a role in the sequel.<ref name=\"blast\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VV7YvoXc82s |title=The On Blast Show Ep10: Katalin Zamiar (Kitana) |publisher=Youtube.com |date=2012-09-06 |accessdate=2014-01-17}}</ref> Zamiar said she was introduced to them through [[Johnny Cage]]'s actor, [[Daniel Pesina]], \"when they decided they wanted to cast a female martial artist for the ninja roles.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Katalin Rodriguez Ogren |url=http://www.chicagonow.com/pow-mixed-martial-arts/2015/04/mortal-kombat-reunion-brings-gamers-from-all-over-the-world-to-chicago/#image/7 |title=Mortal Kombat Still Popular After 20 Years |publisher=Chicagonow.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-20}}</ref> She trained in [[kung fu]] for the first time in preparation for the role.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://lifeofafighter.com/2013/10/the-art-of-martial-arts-katalin-rodriguez-ogren |title=The Art of Martial Arts: Katalin Rodriguez Ogren &#124; Life Of a Fighter - Your source for Health, Fitness, Nutrition, & MMA. Health Advice & Tips, Workouts, MMA News & Training, UFC Gym, Interviews, and more. What's your fight? |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=2013-10-04 |accessdate=2015-05-20 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508055211/http://lifeofafighter.com/2013/10/the-art-of-martial-arts-katalin-rodriguez-ogren/ |archivedate=May 8, 2014 }}</ref> Though Kitana returned for ''UMK3'', Zamiar did not reprise the role due to legal issues with [[Midway Games]]<ref name=\"gamingliberty\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thegamingliberty.com/2011/02/the-97-midway-court-case-shang-tsung-and-kitana-speak|title=The '97 Midway Court Case - Shang Tsung and Kitana Speak!|publisher=The Gaming Liberty|date=February 10, 2011|accessdate=February 2, 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150203100400/http://www.thegamingliberty.com/2011/02/the-97-midway-court-case-shang-tsung-and-kitana-speak/|archivedate=February 3, 2015|df=}}</ref> and was replaced by Becky Gable.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/Tips_Tricks_Volume_III_Issue_01_1996-01_LFP_US/Tips__Tricks_Volume_III_Issue_01_1996-01_LFP_US#page/n15/mode/2up |title=Tips & Tricks - Volume III Issue 1 (1996-01) |publisher=Archive.org |date= |accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref> [[Karen Strassman]], who voiced Kitana in the 2011 reboot, reprised the role for the story mode of ''Mortal Kombat X'', with [[Grey DeLisle]] performing in-gameplay voice work for the character.<ref>{{cite tweet |author= Grey Griffin |user= GreyDeLisle|number= 590327143076208640 |date= April 20, 2015 |title= \"The lovely Karen Strassman had to take over the story lines when I had my baby...but the ass kicking is ALL ME!\" |access-date= April 21, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Kitana Mileena Jade MKSM.png|thumb|Kitana with derived characters [[Jade (Mortal Kombat)|Jade]] (left) and [[Mileena]] (right) in an early concept art for ''[[Mortal Kombat: Shaolin Monks]]''. The three all became popular characters|left]]\n\nUp until ''Mortal Kombat Gold'', Kitana, Mileena and Jade all wore a common costume design in each game, differing from each other through palette swapping (purple for Mileena and green for Jade) to create their digitized [[Sprite (computer graphics)|sprite]] graphics.{{#tag:ref|Jade, when introduced as a secret character in ''MKII'', was a faster recolor of Kitana with green attire and darker skin, using her weapons and attacks. Jade was given her own weapon and distinct special moves in the later games, and was officially written into the storyline in ''UMK3'' as Kitana's friend and fellow Edenian.|group=\"note\"}} Katalin Zamiar's outfit used for all three female ninja characters of ''MKII'' was Kitana's blue.<ref name=\"hugues\">[http://huguesjohnson.com/scans/mk2-behind-scenes/13-katalin-zamiar.jpg VideoGames: The Ultimate Gaming Magazine #63] (April 1994), p. 49.</ref><ref name=mms/> It was a tailor-made, [[swimsuit]]-based<ref name=blast/> simple costume that however presented some challenges for the crew during filming.{{#tag:ref|Such as the bottoms of the leggings being a bit too slippery for moves such as jump kicks<ref>''GamePro'' 58 (May 1994), pages 28-31.</ref> and the tops having to be held up with rubber bands, while her mask was taped to her nose to keep it in place.<ref name=\"hugues\"/>|group=\"note\"}} For ''UMK3'', Becky Gable was videotaped in a more revealing outfit,<ref name=mms>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/mean-machines-sega-magazine-42/MMSega_42_Apr_1996#page/n17/mode/1up/ |title=Mean Machines Sega Magazine Issue 42 |publisher=Archive.org |date= |accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref> which this time was red to stand out from the [[Chroma key|blue screen]] more.<ref>[http://twitpic.com/dlauqw Random MK fun fact] by Ed Boon on TwitPic.</ref> Both of these \"classics\" returned as optional costumes in ''MK2011''.{{#tag:ref|First as an exclusive costume in the pre-order bonuses and then later as paid [[downloadable content]] (DLC).<ref>Michael McWhertor, [http://kotaku.com/5806097/mortal-kombat-adds-klassic-costumes-klassic-fatalities-and-skarlet-with-its-first-dlk \"Mortal Kombat Adds Klassic Costumes, Klassic Fatalities and Skarlet With Its First DLK\"], Kotaku, May 26, 2011.</ref> Classic outfits for Kitana and Jade from ''MKII'', jokingly described by NetherRealm Studios as \"swimsuit party\",<ref>[https://twitter.com/MK_MortalKombat Mortal Kombat (@MK_MortalKombat)] on Twitter.</ref> were also later included as part of a free DLC.<ref>[http://www.thelonegamer.net/dlc/mk2-kitana-and-jade-skins-free-dlc/ MK2 Kitana and Jade Skins Free DLC], TheLoneGamer.Net, July 20th, 2011.</ref>|group=\"note\"}} Kitana first appeared unmasked in her [[3D computer graphics|3D graphics]] model in ''Gold''. In ''Deception'', Kitana appears in the endings for Sindel and Ermac, resembling an unmasked and blue-clad version of Mileena from this game. Kitana's main costume in ''MKX'', notably less skimpy than usual,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cinemablend.com/games/Mortal-Kombat-X-Gameplay-Trailer-Highlights-Kitana-Kung-Lao-69466.html |title=Mortal Kombat X Gameplay Trailer Highlights Kitana, Kung Lao |publisher=Cinemablend.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-20}}</ref> was created to be different than it has been in the previous games.{{#tag:ref|Developer [[NetherRealm Studios]] stated they \"wanted to come up with something exciting and fresh for her look in ''Mortal Kombat X''. Past incarnations have tended to favor the royal qualities of the character over the warrior aspects, so we decided to reverse that for her costume. She has a stealthier, more ninja inspired design with blue as an accent color against the black parts of her costume.\"<ref name=tblr>{{cite web|url=http://netherrealmstudios.tumblr.com/post/110837056578/kitana-is-a-signature-member-of-the-mortal-kombat |title=Mortal Kombat X, Kitana is a signature member of the Mortal Kombat |publisher=Netherrealmstudios.tumblr.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-20}}</ref>|group=\"note\"}} Her alternative costume in ''MKX'' is more in the style of her previous outfits.<ref name=\"twitter.com\">{{cite tweet|user=noobde|author=Ed Boon|number=566257834749218816|date=13 February 2015|title=In case U missed yesterday's Mortal Kombat X twitch stream, here is the archived video on YouTube. Reptile &amp; Kitana!}}</ref>\n\nBesides Mileena and Jade in ''Mortal Kombat II'' and [[Khameleon]] in ''Mortal Kombat Trilogy'', another character, Tanya, who was introduced in ''[[Mortal Kombat 4]]'', also began as a recolored version of Kitana with altered moves.<ref name=den/> Another character derived from Kitana is the crimson code-colored female ninja [[Skarlet (Mortal Kombat)|Skarlet]], who was first rumored to be an [[Ermac]]-style [[glitch]] character and debuted as a playable in ''MK2011''.<ref name=den>{{cite web|author=Gavin Jasper |url=http://www.denofgeek.us/games/mortal-kombat/241361/mortal-kombat-the-definitive-guide-to-the-secret-characters |title=Mortal Kombat: The Definitive Guide to the Secret Characters |publisher=Denofgeek.us |date= |accessdate=2015-07-01}}</ref> The moveset of Sonya Blade in ''Mortal Kombat 3'' is very similar to Kitana's in ''MKII''.<ref>''Mean Machine Sega'' 33 (July 1995) page 21.</ref>\n\nKitana's official measurements in ''Deadly Alliance'' are 128 lb. weight and 5'9\" height.<ref>''PlayStation 2 Official Magazine-Australia'' issue 15, page 85.</ref> Her weapon of choice is a pair of razor-edged steel fans, inspired by [[Japanese war fan]]s and originally being fully metal. Kitana's fans during the production of ''MKII'' were not actually steel but made of a reflective paper material, and were Zamiar's own training fans.<ref name=ppa>Benedykt Dziuba\u0142towski, [http://www.ppa.pl/gry/interview-with-katalin-ogren-an-actress-played-a-character-of-kitana-mileena-and-jade-in-mortal-kombat-2.html Interview with Katalin Ogren - an actress played a character of Kitana, Mileena and Jade in \"Mortal Kombat 2\"], PPA.pl, 09.11.2012.</ref> Following her ''MKII'' debut, Kitana was repeatedly removed from further sequels due to various circumstances, only to always return in a port or an update, as it was the case with ''UMK3''/''Trilogy'' after her absence in ''MK3'', ''Gold'' after her absence in ''MK4'', and ''[[Mortal Kombat: Unchained]]'' after her absence in ''Deception''.{{#tag:ref|The ''MKII''-style (albeit modified and noticeably different for all of them) costumes for Kitana, Mileena and Jade have been actually considered to return already in ''Shaolin Monks'', as seen in early concept art<ref name=\"totalmortalkombat.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.totalmortalkombat.com/mksm/art/jade_kitana_mileena_concept.jpg |title='&#39;Shaolin Monks'&#39; concept art for Kitana, Mileena and Jade |date= |accessdate=2014-01-17}}</ref> for this game, but was rejected in favor of fresher designs (in Kitana's case, it meant a cross between her attire from ''UMK3'' and ''Deadly Alliance'').|group=\"note\"}} In ''Gold'', Kitana uses a throwing weapon, the \"Flying Blade,\" which is similar to Tanya's sharp boomerang due to the two characters' linked development history in the original version of ''MK4''.{{#tag:ref|Kitana was included in early development versions of ''MK4'', before her character model (shown only in Liu Kang's ending; she also appears in his ending in the original ''MK3'') became basis for creating Tanya, and is accessible to play in the [[Nintendo 64]] version of the game with the use of [[GameShark]] and [[Action Replay]] cheat cartridge devices.<ref>\"Nintendo 64 Official tips\". ''Nintendo Official Magazine'' 74, page 83.</ref>|group=\"note\"}} In ''MKX'', Kitana can use either her own weapons or those of Jade from previous games: a telescoping staff, and a [[glaive]] throwing blade that is guidable in midflight.\n\nMost of Kitana's traditional special moves utilize her twin fan weapons, used as a melee weapon, as a thrown projectile, and to lift her enemies in the air.{{#tag:ref|During the early production runs of ''Mortal Kombat II'', Kitana became notorious as an unbeatable kombatant, as her \"Fan Lift\" special attack could be done in such a way as to completely immobilize the opponent in the corner of the screen, allowing the player to defeat their opponent with a series of uncontested attacks. Changes were made to eliminate this and balance the game, yet still Ed Boon said that it was amazing seeing people doing combos with her that even he had not thought of.<ref name=kk/>|group=\"note\"}} In later games, Kitana received some special moves that have been typically associated with Mileena, such as a ground-roll attack in ''vs. DC Universe'' and [[teleportation]]-based moves since ''Shaolin Monks''. Like all playable characters in ''Mortal Kombat X'', Kitana has three different style variations to choose from in this game, including her \"Mournful\" variation using Jade's special attacks such as \"Shadow Kick\" and weapons. Her other ''MKX'' styles are the aggressive, fast and acrobatic Assassin, and the defensively-oriented Royal Storm, which expands on her fan-lifting abilities.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lazygamer.net/general-news/get-konnected-with-kitana-in-mortal-kombat-x/|title=Get konnected with Kitana in Mortal Kombat X|last=Bonthuys|first=Darryn|date=February 25, 2015|publisher=LazyGamer.net|accessdate=May 7, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Gameplay====\nKitana was chosen as the best ''Mortal Kombat II'' fighter by the editors of ''[[Sega Power]]'' and ''[[Super Play]]'' for being \"good all around\" and due to her quick attacks and perceived similarities to [[Chun-Li]].<ref name=ap>\"True Stories: Mortal Kombat 2\". [http://amr.abime.net/issue_44 Amiga Power'' 44] (December 1994), pages 10-11.</ref> ''[[Amiga Power]]'' too called her \"a really good character to pick\"<ref name=ap/> and Cinema Blend stated Kitana \"could absolutely dominate\" the game.<ref>{{cite web|url = https://www.cinemablend.com/games/Top-10-Best-Fighting-Games-Of-All-Time-13864.html|title = Top 10 Best Fighting Games Of All Time|date = December 7, 2008|accessdate = April 3, 2013}}</ref> However, ''[[GamePro]]'s'' strategy guide ranked Kitana as only the seventh best of the 12 fighters in ''MKII'' (citing her devastating [[Combo (video gaming)|combos]], powerful \"Fan Throw\" move, and good sweep and reach hindered by slow release of the fan-based special moves and limited attack patterns); it was her clone Mileena who landed on the top of their chart.<ref>\"ProStrategy Guide: Mortal Kombat II\". ''GamePro'' 59 (June 1994), pages 82-83.</ref> According to a retrospective by ''[[Complex (magazine)|Complex]]'', Kitana \"had the most powerful projectile attack, and along with Mileena, the fastest throws and sweeps.\"<ref name=wong/> \"Kitana's big combos in the corner\" were among Ed Boon's own personal favourite things in the game: \"When I saw people do Kitana's combos I knew there was something special, because people were taking the game to a new direction.\"<ref>''GamePro'' 59 (June 1994), page 120.</ref> ''[[Electronic Gaming Monthly|EGM]]'' described Kitana as \"a force to be reckoned with\" and predicted she would \"make a big impact as her Fan Wave leaves foes open to combos.\"<ref>''Electronic Gaming Monthly'' issue 54 (January 1994), page 192.</ref> In the [[Game Gear]] version of ''MKII'', however, Kitana's fan lifts the opponent too low and too far away for an easy combo.<ref>Slasher Quan, ''GamePro'' issue 63 (October 1994), page 40.</ref>\n\nKitana's combo abilities were severely downgraded for ''Ultimate Mortal Kombat 3'' (and, by extension, ''Mortal Kombat Trilogy''), for which she received no new special moves unlike most of the other characters. According to ''[[Nintendo Power]]'', \"with such a small repertoire, Princess Kitana will be sorely challenged by experienced warriors,\" even as her fan toss is faster than many other projectile attacks.<ref>\"Full Coverage: Ultimate Mortal Kombat 3\". ''Nintendo Power'' 91 (December 1996), page 71.</ref> ''[[Sega Saturn Magazine]]'' opined that \"Kitana's lack of enhancements doesn't make her as exciting to play as some of the other characters, though her excellent juggle combos still work - and they can do loads of damage,\"<ref name=ossm>\"Showcases: Mortal Kombat 3\". ''Official Sega Saturn Magazine'' 6 (April 1996), page 47.</ref> According to ''Total 64'', \"her moves are a little unfriendly and her combos are a touch difficult.\"<ref name=total/> ''EGM Strategy Guide'' for ''UMK3'' stated: \"She had deadly corner traps with damage in up to 90 percent [in ''MKII'']. Now, her fan-raise combos have been severely crippled to almost not being worth it.\" Nevertheless, ''[[X-One|X360]]'' called the [[CPU]] Kitana \"the worst possible character to come up against\" in the single-player Tower mode of ''UMK3'', as she is \"fast, impossible to sweep, and capable of rendering any opponent incapable with a waft of her fan.\"<ref name=x360>{{cite web|author=The X360 Magazine Team |url=http://www.x360magazine.com/general/an-alternative-top-ten-females-in-gaming/ |title=An Alternative Top Ten Females In Gaming |publisher=X360magazine.com |date=2009-08-24 |accessdate=2014-01-17}}</ref> According to ''Dreamcast Magazine'', ''Mortal Kombat Gold'''s returning \"old favourites like Sub-Zero, Kitana and Baraka\" too had by then \"dated moves and fatalities.\"<ref>Allex Warren, \"Mortal Kombat Gold\". ''Dreamcast Magazine'' issue 32, page 21.</ref> Her combos improved in the later games, and according to [[BradyGames]]' official guide for ''Mortal Kombat: Deadly Alliance'', \"Kitana stays at the top of the heap as far as kombatants go. In any stance, she can pump out over 30% with relative ease, making her one of the deadliest in the hands of a beginner or a master.\"<ref>Ben Cureton, Paul Edwards, ''Mortal Kombat: Deadly Alliance Official Strategy Guide'', BradyGames 2002 (p.17).</ref> Kitana was later found to be capable of infinite-loop corner combos in her \"Mournful\" variation in ''Mortal Kombat X''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eventhubs.com/news/2015/apr/28/mournful-kitanas-glave-gives-her-multiple-infinite-loop-combos-mortal-kombat-x/ |title=Mournful Kitana's glave gives her multiple infinite loop combos in Mortal Kombat X |publisher=Eventhubs.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://shoryuken.com/2015/04/28/try-not-to-cry-mournful-kitana-has-corner-infinites-in-mortal-kombat-x/ |title=Try Not to Cry; Mournful Kitana Has Corner Infinites in Mortal Kombat X |publisher=Shoryuken.com |date=2015-04-28 |accessdate=2015-05-18}}</ref>\n\nIn ''Mortal Kombat:'' ''Shaolin Monks'', Kitana is fought as a [[Boss (video gaming)|boss character]] twice in the game's main story mode and is one of [[Unlockable (gaming)|unlockable]] player characters for the versus mode. [[Prima Games]]' guide to ''Shaolin Monks'' states she is \"quick enough for moderate damage, and has some of the most potent special moves in the game,\" but her limitation is she needs to be fighting at close range to make an use of it.<ref>Eric Mylonas, ''Mortal Kombat: Shaolin Monks (Prima Official Guide)'', Prima Games 2005 (p.111).</ref> Regarding ''Mortal Kombat: Armageddon'', however, Prima declared Kitana \"a tough character to win with\" and \"like many of the other low tier character types, she's lacking in almost every aspect\" (even as she \"is a little better on defense than she is on offense\"). She was rated overall only 4/10 for this game.<ref>Bryan Dawson, ''Mortal Kombat: Armageddon (Prima Official Game Guide)'', Prima Games 2006 (p.198-201).</ref> Their official guide for ''Mortal Kombat vs. DC Universe'', on the other hand, called her \"one of the more dangerous characters in the game due to her speed and extremely effective move-set.\"<ref>Jason Wilson, ''Mortal Kombat vs. DC Universe: Prima Official Game Guide'', Prima Games 2008 (p.102).</ref> Prima's official guide for 2011's ''Mortal Kombat'' deemed Kitana a capable fighter who once again \"is at her deadliest in the corner\" and is also especially good if played against [[Baraka (Mortal Kombat)|Baraka]] and [[Sub-Zero (Mortal Kombat)|Cyber Sub-Zero]].<ref>Jason Wilson, Adam Hernandez, ''Mortal Kombat: Prima Official Game Guide'', Prima Games 2011 (p.123).</ref> Prima observed Kitana in ''MK2011'' as her \"cheapest\" (unduly overpowered) incarnation so far, stating \"Kitana is not only one of the most damaging characters in the game, but in addition to the Fan Lift and Square Wave Punch, she can combo her Air Fan almost any time an opponent is airborne.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.primagames.com/games/mortal-kombat-x/feature/cheapest-characters-mortal-kombat-history-part-2|title=Cheapest Characters in Mortal Kombat History: Part 2|work=Prima Games|accessdate=May 11, 2015}}</ref> According to Prima's guide to ''MKX'', \"Kitana is one of the more unique characters in the game\" due to her inheriting many of Jade's special moves, and she \"is a zoning character at heart, but she can play offensively or defensively\" depending of a variation chosen. The guide recommended the \"Mournful\" variant for former Jade players, and the \"Assassin\" variant, which \"tries to take the generally defensive style Kitana has in ''MKX'' and add some offensive firepower to it,\" for veteran Kitana players.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.primagames.com/games/mortal-kombat-x/tips/mortal-kombat-x-how-play-kitana-combos-and-strategies |title=Mortal Kombat X - How to Play Kitana: Combos and Strategies &#124; Tips |publisher=Primagames.com |date=2015-04-14 |accessdate=2015-05-18}}</ref>\n\n===Other media===\nKitana appears in [[Malibu Comics]]'s 1994-1995 [[Mortal Kombat (Malibu Comics)|''Mortal Kombat'']] comic book series. She first appears during the 1994 three-issue miniseries ''Goro: Prince of Pain'', joining Mileena, Baraka and [[Reptile (Mortal Kombat)|Reptile]] in searching for Goro in Outworld. During the ''Battlewave'' miniseries, she attempts to rebel against Kahn with the assistance of Kung Lao, Baraka and Sub-Zero. Kitana's enemies besides Mileena include Scorpion, who offers to take her as his new wife. She is the subject of a one-shot issue titled ''Kitana and Mileena: Sister Act'', in which her royal background from the games is intact, only she is already an adult when Shao Kahn kills Jerrod and seizes the realm, before putting her under a spell that makes her forget her past life and instead believe she is Kahn's daughter. Unlike in the game series' continuity, in the comic series Kitana has no interactions with neither Liu Kang nor Jade; instead, she has a closer relation with Kung Lao (Shang Tsung even attempts to exploit this while taking Kitana's form).<ref>''Mortal Kombat: Kung Lao #1: \"Rising Son\"'' (p.10-12).</ref> In [[Mortal Kombat (comics)|the official comics]], Kitana has a small part in Midway's ''Mortal Kombat 4'' prologue comic book published in 1997 and released with the PC version of the game, in which she arranges peace between the warring Shokan and Centaurian races, and appears in the 2008 tie-in comic ''Mortal Kombat vs. DC Universe: Beginnings'', illustrated John Tobias and published by [[DC Comics]] in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comicvine.com/mortal-kombat-vs-dc-universe-beginnings/37-150618/|title=Mortal Kombat VS DC Universe #1 - Beginnings (comic book issue)|date=2008-11-01|publisher=Comicvine.com|accessdate=2013-11-06}}</ref>[[File:Movie Kitana.png|thumb|upright|[[Talisa Soto]] as Kitana in the 1995 film ''[[Mortal Kombat (1995 film)|Mortal Kombat]]''. According to producer Lauri Apelian, \"with Talisa and [[Bridgette Wilson|Bridgette [Wilson]]], we had two characters that were well rounded. I didn't want the women to be cardboard characters. They needed to have a strength and an independence and an intellect that went well beyond their beauty and being sexy.\"<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/mortal-kombat-movie-oral-history-815287 |title='Mortal Kombat': Untold Story of the Movie That \"Kicked the Hell\" Out of Everyone |work=The Hollywood Reporter|access-date=2018-11-24|language=en}}</ref>|alt=This image shows a black-haired woman with braided hair, wearing an all-black outfit with a corset top, pants and elbows-long handless gloves.]]\n\nDespite being a major character in the video games' storyline, Princess Kitana was only a supporting character in both ''Mortal Kombat'' live-action films. In the movies, Kitana was portrayed by [[Talisa Soto]] (who was one of the only two actors, along with [[Robin Shou]], to play the same character in both films), who was unmasked and wore less revealing, all-black costumes. In the 1995 [[Mortal Kombat (1995 film)|first film]], Kitana is introduced as a companion of Shang Tsung, who is aware that she is a dangerous adversary due to her being the rightful heir of Outworld and may attempt to ally herself with the Earth fighters, and he therefore sends Reptile to spy on Kitana. She eventually joins Liu Kang and the Earthrealm warriors to help them defeat the sorcerer. In the 1995 novelization of the first ''Mortal Kombat'' film by [[Martin Delrio]], based in part on the early scripts by Kevin Droney,{{#tag:ref|In the second draft script from April 1994, Kitana is described as \"an exotic woman of startling beauty\" and \"powerful legs\", who uses \"kung fu and [[aikido]]\" in combat. She wears white garments at one point and plays a much bigger role in the film's finale, after which she does kiss Liu.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tabmok99.mortalkombatonline.com/mk_movie_script.doc |title=''Mortal Kombat'' second draft script|first= Kevin |last=Droney |date=April 25, 1994 |accessdate=August 1, 2012}}</ref>|group=\"note\"}} Shang Tsung informs Goro that Kitana \"alone keeps alive the memory\" of the Outworld throne before Kahn's conquest and \"uses her age and her position as a shield to cover her rebellion.\"<ref>''Mortal Kombat: The Movie'' by Martin Delrio, ch. 8.</ref> Kitana spends most of the 1997 sequel ''[[Mortal Kombat: Annihilation]]'' in Kahn's captivity after being captured by [[Scorpion (Mortal Kombat)|Scorpion]], before she faces Sindel during the final battle. Kitana was supposed to appear in the third film as well.\n\nKitana's steel folding fans (redesigned into several individual blades instead of solid all-metal) appear once as her weapon in the films, though she fights with them closed. While ''Annihilation'' teases a romantic relationship between Kitana and Liu Kang, her background in both films consists only of her being the rightful heir to the Outworld throne. They do kiss at the end of ''Annihilation'', and their kiss was actually supposed to be included in the first film too but the director [[Paul W. S. Anderson]] did not like it.<ref>{{Citation|last=tabmok99|title=Q&A Session with the Cast of Mortal Kombat: Annihilation|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=n7QtD-jvjsc|access-date=2018-12-23}}.</ref> The actress Talisa Soto, who said she \"loved\" the character for Kitana's \"incredible strength\" and for the challenge this role posed for her,<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=|title=Fighting Femmes of Mortal Kombat|url=https://archive.org/details/Femme_Fatales_v06n07/page/n7|journal=Femme Fatales|volume=6|issue=7|pages=8|via=}}</ref> said that was while first preparing for her role she was \"educated\" about it by her nieces and nephews.<ref name=\":0\">James Brady, \"In Step With Talisa Soto\", ''Kingman Daily Miner'', July 9, 1995.</ref> She then underwent five weeks of martial arts training in [[tai chi chuan]] and [[wing chun]],<ref name=\":0\" /> while her further role in ''Annihilation'' required her to learn Brazilian [[stick fighting]] for the use of fans.<ref>Lloyd Paseman, 'Kombat' Mortally Wounded, ''Eugene Register-Guard'', December 12, 1997.</ref>\n\nPrincess Kitana is a main character in the 1996 television animated series ''[[Mortal Kombat: Defenders of the Realm]]'', a loose adaptation of ''Mortal Kombat 3'' influenced by the film, where she is voiced by [[Cree Summer]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/starlog_magazine-231/starlog_231#page/n7/mode/1up/|title=Starlog Magazine Issue 231|date=|publisher=Archive.org|accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref> In the series, Kitana in brown-haired and almost always unmasked, wearing a black costume mixing her outfits in ''Mortal Kombat II'' and ''Ultimate Mortal Kombat 3''. Like in the first film, no reference is made to any past loyalty to Kahn. Sean Catherine Derek's Writer Guide document for the show, as well as the official character guide,<ref>http://wskel.com/MK/mk_dotr_1996/show_guide/kombatants/booklet.pdf</ref> describe Kitana as an \"exotic\", \"gorgeous and outrageously sexy\" woman, who is \"extremely mysterious\" as she \"often speaks in mystical riddles.\" The guides also note \"a strong bond and major heat\" between her and Liu Kang, and that \"though she is incredibly feminine, Kitana is a fierce warrior.\" In the episode \"Skin Deep\", [[Rain (Mortal Kombat)|Rain]] is introduced as her former love interest turned enemy, though neither have ever shared any relationship in the series canon other than their Edenian heritage. In the episode \"Swords of Ilkan\", Kitana defeats her former ally named Zara, an original character. The episode \"Abandoned\" features a ninja girl named Ruby, a friend of Kitana (a reworking of Jade). The final episode \"Overthrown\" involves Kitana leading an unsuccessful rebellion against Shao Kahn's Outworld rule.\n\nKitana is a recurring character in the 1998 live-action television series ''[[Mortal Kombat: Conquest]]'', played by [[Audie England]] in two episodes (\"Vengeance\" and \"Shadow of a Doubt\") and once by Dara Tomanovich (\"The Essence\"), with Christine Rodriguez serving as their stunt double.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mortalkombat.com/film-conquestcredits.shtml|title=Full Cast and Crew for \"Mortal Kombat: Conquest\" (1998)|author=Manna Studio|date=2010-12-20|publisher=Web.archive.org|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20101220232155/http://mortalkombat.com/film-conquestcredits.shtml|archivedate=2010-12-20|accessdate=2013-11-06}}</ref> In this series, she is fully aware of her Edenian past and the deaths of her parents at Kahn's hands, clandestinely working with [[Kung Lao]] to prevent the Emperor from conquering realms while at the same time feigning her allegiance to him. Her outfit and weapon are resembling these she has in the films, but she uses her native Edenian fighting style which she had mastered already before Shao Kahn's invasion and which was supplemented with various moves that she learnt from prisoners of her stepfather. The ''Konquest'' version of Mileena is neither her clone nor a sister but just someone who impersonates her to seduce and assassinate Kung Lao, and Rain appears as Kitana's former best friend. In the series finale, which ended in a cliffhanger due to the show's abrupt cancellation after two seasons, Kitana appears to die after she is reluctantly ordered by Shao Kahn to be killed for plotting against him. She is promptly attacked by Shadow Priests and one of them uses Kitana's own fan against her.\n\nKitana was featured in a two-part episode in the 2011 prequel live-action webisode series ''[[Mortal Kombat: Legacy]]''.<ref>[http://kotaku.com/5734272/that-incredible-mortal-kombat-trailer-is-now-a-series \"That Incredible Mortal Kombat Trailer Is Now A Series\"], Kotaku, January 14, 2011.</ref> Kitana was played by martial artist and stuntwoman [[Samantha Jo]] (credited as Sam Tjhia) in her acting debut.<ref>Ian Fisher, [http://www.shogungamer.com/news/find-out-whos-playing-princess-kitana-mortal-kombat-rebirth \"Sam Tjhia Will Play Princess Kitana in Mortal Kombat: Rebirth\"], Shogun Gamer, 03/22/2011.</ref> Jo, a self-professed Kitana fan since her childhood,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Svj3RBo7RnQ |title=Samantha Jo Gets Her Game On As Kitana In Mortal Kombat Legacy 2 - Gamerhubtv |publisher=Youtube.com |date=2013-07-20 |accessdate=2013-10-15}}</ref> said that while preparing for the role she had did research \"to get on the same page\" with fans to see how they perceive Kitana. She said that the hardest part for her was \"to understand the [[sibling rivalry]] and betrayal that Kitana faced in her past, and how it deeply affected the character she is now.\"<ref name=\"sg\">Ian Fisher, [http://shogungamer.com/news/exclusive-interview-actress-sam-tjhia-mortal-kombat-legacy \"Exclusive Interview With Actress Sam Tjhia (Mortal Kombat: Legacy)\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180311023602/http://shogungamer.com/news/exclusive-interview-actress-sam-tjhia-mortal-kombat-legacy |date=2018-03-11 }}, Shogun Gamer, 05/03/2011.</ref> Kitana's origin is told in part-live and part-animated episode \"Kitana & Mileena\", which is an altered adaptation of their backstory from the original game series' canon. In a notable difference, her mother Sindel uses a ritual so her soul fuses with Kitana's in hopes to avoid Shao Kahn's corruption before committing suicide. Kitana appears both masked (only in the animated scenes) and unmasked, and bests Mileena in a fierce sparring match. When the young sisters are sent by Shao Kahn to assassinate the man who is really King Jerrod, Kitana's biological father who is killed by Mileena, Kitana eventually learns the truth after her past and decides to turn against Shao Kahn in the upcoming Mortal Kombat tournament. Kitana returned for the second season of ''Legacy'' in 2013,<ref>Eric Goldman, [https://uk.ign.com/articles/2012/07/14/comic-con-mortal-kombat-legacy-season-2-is-coming-2 Comic-Con: Mortal Kombat Legacy Season 2 is Coming], IGN, July 14, 2012.</ref> still played by Sam Jo but in a new costume.{{#tag:ref|Kitana's new outfit was revealed by director [[Kevin Tancharoen]].<ref>[http://instagram.com/p/TKREnTs6D8/ Kitana] on Kevin Tancharoen's Twitter account \"ktach\".</ref> Jo also featured in a clip titled \"Kitana's Lost Fan\" as promotion for the second season.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Kr_TQLGzE2U |title=Kitana's Lost Fan - This is Mortal Kombat |publisher=YouTube |date=2013-09-26 |accessdate=2013-11-01}}</ref>|group=\"note\"}} In the second season, Kitana comes to rescue of Johnny Cage by fighting and defeating Mileena, whom she decapitates.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://uk.ign.com/articles/2013/07/19/comic-con-mortal-kombat-legacy-season-2-and-season-3-info |title=Comic-Con: Mortal Kombat: Legacy Season 2 and Season 3 Info: Get Ready for Fatalities|first=Jim|last=McMahon|work=IGN|date=July 19, 2013}}</ref>\n\nKitana was among several characters featured in the 1995 stage show ''[[Mortal Kombat: Live Tour]]'', where she was played by [[Lexi Alexander]] (credited as Lexi Mirai)<ref>[http://www.keramcast.com/keramcast-episode-nine/ Epi 9 Interview with Director Lexi Alexander], KeramCast.com, December 12, 2008.</ref><ref name=\"bb\">''Black Belt'' Vol. 41, No. 6 (June 2003).</ref> and Jennifer DeCosta. Kitana, played by [[Dana Hee]], was also featured in [[Threshold Entertainment]]'s abortive web show ''Mortal Kombat: Federation of Martial Arts'' in 2000-2001, where she fought against Johnny Cage and Scorpion before the show was canceled.\n\n===Promotion and merchandise===\nModel Rachelle Glover<ref>[http://guyspeed.com/hot-girl-mortal-kombal-kitana-ps-vita-commercial/ Who Is The Hot Girl In Mortal Kombat's \"Kitana\" Commercial?], GuySpeed, April 30, 2012.</ref> dressed as Kitana, along with others dressed as Sonya and Mileena, was featured in her a 2011 live-action trailer \"Kitana Kasting\" and an official photo session;<ref name=\"g4tv.com\">Nikole Zivalich, [http://www.g4tv.com/thefeed/blog/post/711704/mortal-kombat-sexy-cosplay-sonya-blade-kitana-and-mileena/ Mortal Kombat Sexy Cosplay -- Sonya Blade, Kitana And Mileena], G4tv.com, April 8, 2011.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mortalkombatonline.com/content/News/read.cds?article=1667 |title=Live-Action Jade & Skarlet Featured in Russian Vita Advertising |publisher=Mortalkombatonline.com |date=2012-05-18 |accessdate=2014-01-17}}<br>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamestar.pl/news/369155/Seksowne.modelki.promuja.Mortal.Kombat.html|title= Sexy models promote Mortal Kombat|first=Jakub |last=Kuchnio|publisher= Gamestar.pl|date=April 12, 2011|accessdate=September 7, 2014}}</ref> all three of them later attended ''[[The Gadget Show: World Tour]]'' for a ''MK'' game tournament.<ref name=\"g4tv.com\"/> Glover also portrayed Kitana in 2012's \"Play Anywhere\", a live-action trailer for the [[PlayStation Vita]] version of ''Mortal Kombat'', first in two teaser trailers and then in the full version with both of them mixed together.<ref>David Hinkle, [http://www.joystiq.com/2012/04/13/mortal-kombat-ps-vita-live-action-trailer-suggests-theres-a-lit/ Mortal Kombat PS Vita live action trailer suggests there's a little Kitana in all of us], Joystiq, April 13, 2012.<br>Erskin Hansen, [http://www.caribbeangamezone.com/news/gaming/mortal-kombat-ps-vita-mileena-kitana-live-action-trailer/ Mortal Kombat PS Vita Mileena & Kitana Live Action Trailer], Caribbean Game-Zone, April 25, 2012.</ref> Also to promote ''MK2011,'' [[Ultimate Fighting Championship|UFC]]'s Octagon Girl [[Brittney Palmer]] dressed up in a blue costume and played as Kitana in the game in a ''[[Playboy]]'' vlog.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.playboy.com/articles/jo-garcia-battles-ufc-octagon-girl-brittney-palmer/index.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110422111021/http://www.playboy.com/articles/jo-garcia-battles-ufc-octagon-girl-brittney-palmer/index.html |archivedate=2011-04-22 |title=Jo Garcia in Mortal Kombat vs. UFC Octagon Girl Brittney Palmer (Video) - Sexy Photo Gallery |publisher=Web.archive.org |date= |accessdate=2014-01-17}}<br>Anthony Severino, [http://www.gamerevolution.com/news/flawless-playboy-vixens-fight-for-mortal-kombat-victory-5211 \"Flawless Playboy Vixens Fight For Mortal Kombat Victory\"], Game Revolution, April 19, 2011.</ref>\n\nA figurine of Kitana came in the ''MKII'' set with the Argentinian magazine ''Top Kids'' in 1995.<ref>{{cite web|author=Juan Quaglia |url=http://www.juguetesdecoleccion.com/guia-del-coleccionista/munecos-de-mortal-kombat-top-kids/ |title=Mu\u00f1ecos de Mortal Kombat Top Kids &#124; Gu\u00eda del coleccionista |publisher=Juguetesdecoleccion.com |date=2013-05-31 |accessdate=2014-01-17}}</ref> An action figure of Kitana was released in the UK by Toy Island as part of their 1996 ''Mortal Kombat Trilogy'' series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.videogamemm.com/main/content/mortal-kombat-trilogy-series-2-kitana-figure |title=Mortal Kombat Trilogy Series 2 Kitana Figure |publisher=Videogamemm.com |date= |accessdate=2014-01-17}}</ref> Another action figure of Kitana, this time in her ''MKX'' \"Royal Storm\" variation, was released by [[Mezco Toyz]] in 2015<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mezcotoyz.com/mortal-kombat-x-series-2-kitana |title=Mortal Kombat X Series 2: KITANA \u2013 Mezco Toyz |publisher=Mezcotoyz.com |date= |accessdate=2015-05-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518081258/http://www.mezcotoyz.com/mortal-kombat-x-series-2-kitana |archivedate=2015-05-18 |df= }}</ref> and a [[Funko|Funko Pop!]] figure was released in 2017<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://nerdreactor.com/2017/09/13/mortal-kombat-funko-pop/|title=Mortal Kombat is getting Funko Pop! vinyl figures - Nerd Reactor|date=2017-09-13|work=Nerd Reactor|access-date=2018-05-23|language=en-US}}</ref> followed by a more realistic Funko action figure,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.funko.com/products/all/brands/action-figure/action-figures-mortal-kombat-kitana|website=www.funko.com|title=Action Figures: Mortal Kombat - Kitana|access-date=2018-12-25}}</ref> both also of the \"Royal Storm\". A 1/6-scale limited-edition statue of Kitana from ''MK2011'' was released by Syco Collectibles in the Enchanted Warriors series in 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sycocollectibles.com/search?tid=All&title=kitana |title=Kitana Polystone Statue |publisher=Sycocollectibles.com |date= |accessdate=2014-01-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140118192056/http://www.sycocollectibles.com/search?tid=All&title=kitana |archivedate=2014-01-18 |df= }}</ref> A 1/4 scale statue by Pop Culture Shock Collectibles was released in 2013,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://toynewsi.com/news.php?itemid=19608|title=Pop Culture Shock Announces Mortal Kombat 9 Kitana 1:4 scale statue|website=toynewsi.com|language=en|access-date=2018-05-23}}</ref> including an unmasked limited edition.<ref>Luke Plunkett, [http://kotaku.com/5970385/355-will-get-you-your-very-own-20-mortal-kombat-femme-fatale/gallery/1 $355 Will Get You Your Very Own Giant Mortal Kombat Femme Fatale], Kotaku, December 24, 2012.</ref> A 1/3 scale statue of Kitana from ''MKX'' was released by Pop Culture Shock in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.popcultureshocktoys.com/en/kitana-13-statue-mortal-kombat-x-2|title=Kitana MKX 1:3|website=PCS Collectibles|access-date=2018-05-23}}</ref> Besides figures, some of them unreleased,{{#tag:ref|One unreleased action figure based on her ''MKII'' design and an earlier figure of Mileena was presented by Infinite Concepts in a prototype form at the [[American International Toy Fair]] 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.toymania.com/toyfair2000/infinite/infinite2000.shtml|title=Infinite Concepts Toy Fair 2000 Coverage|date=|publisher=Toymania.com|accessdate=2014-01-17}}</ref>|group=\"note\"}} there have been also a number of other Kitana-themed merchandise items.'''{{#tag:ref|Kitana was one of several ''MK'' characters featured on 2.5\" x 3.5\" collectible magnets by Ata-Boy Wholesale in 2011.<ref>[http://ataboy.cameoez.com/images/import/29999MK.jpg Kitana 2.5\" x 3.5\" magnet] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160108205815/http://ataboy.cameoez.com/images/import/29999MK.jpg |date=2016-01-08 }} - Ata-Boy Wholesale, 2011. Retrieved February 26, 2014.</ref> A 3-D mousepad was also released.<ref>[http://www.geekologie.com/2013/01/well-endowed-mortal-kombat-kitana-mousep.php Well Endowed Mortal Kombat Kitana Mousepad], Geekologie, January 30, 2013.</ref> [[Io9]]'s Charlie Jane Anders listed a costume of Kitana among 2011's \"[[slut]]tiest and weirdest\" store-bought Halloween costumes,<ref>Charlie Jane Anders, [http://io9.com/5852860/this-years-sluttiest-and-weirdest-store+bought-halloween-costumes/gallery/1 This Year's Sluttiest and Weirdest Store-Bought Halloween Costumes] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121017235812/http://io9.com/5852860/this-years-sluttiest-and-weirdest-store+bought-halloween-costumes/gallery/1 |date=2012-10-17 }}, io9, October 24, 2011.</ref> but Justin Amirikhani of ''Complex'' praised it as one of \"last-minute video game costumes that actually look cool\"<ref>Justin Amirikhani, [http://www.complex.com/video-games/2012/10/15-last-minute-video-game-game-costumes-that-actually-look-cool/mileena-kitana-and-sonya-blade 15 Last-Minute Video Game Game Costumes That Actually Look Cool], Complex.com, October 23, 2012.</ref> and Brian Altano of [[IGN]] included it among \"ten ridiculous (or ridiculously sexy) video game inspired Halloween costumes\" of 2012.<ref>Brian Altano, [https://uk.ign.com/articles/2012/10/22/the-most-ridiculous-sexy-video-game-costumes-of-2012 The Most Ridiculous, Sexy Video Game Costumes of 2012], IGN, October 22, 2012.</ref>|group=\"note\"}}'''\n\n== Cultural impact ==\nKitana appeared in two issues of the humor magazine ''[[Cracked (magazine)|Cracked]]'' (in which she was renamed \"Princess Kittykat\")<ref>Lifestyles of the Rich and Violent\" (1994) and \"Moron Kombat\" (1995) in ''Cracked'' #291 (August 1994) and #303 (November 1995).</ref> and in [[Grant Ginder]]'s 2009 novel ''This Is How It Starts''.<ref>[http://books.simonandschuster.com/This-Is-How-It-Starts/Grant-Ginder/9781416595595 Ginder, Grant. ''This Is How It Starts''] (p.187). Simon and Schuster (2009), {{ISBN|9781416595595}}</ref> The video-game versions of wrestlers [[The Bella Twins]] in the 2015 game ''[[WWE Immortals]]'' were dressed in costumes inspired by Mileena and Kitana.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://au.ibtimes.com/wwe-immortals-gameplay-roster-revealed-1409252|archive-url=https://archive.today/20150204234340/http://au.ibtimes.com/wwe-immortals-gameplay-roster-revealed-1409252|url-status=dead|archive-date=February 4, 2015|title=WWE Immortals: Gameplay and Roster Revealed|first=Nicolo|last=Parungo|website=International Business Times|date=January 12, 2015|accessdate=February 10, 2015}}</ref> Musician [[Princess Nokia]] (Destiny Nicole Frasqueri), who named Kitana as her favourite female game character, made a 2017 song titled \"Kitana\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.factmag.com/2017/09/28/level-up-princess-nokia/|title=Level Up: Princess Nokia on how the video game community unites the freaks and geeks|date=2017-09-28|work=FACT Magazine: Music News, New Music.|access-date=2018-05-23|language=en-US}}<br>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ok-tho.com/2017/04/princess-nokia-and-girl-space-at.html|title=Princess Nokia and Girl Space at Brooklyn Bazaar|website=www.ok-tho.com|access-date=2018-05-23}}</ref>\n\nSince the early 1990s,'''{{#tag:ref|One early Kitana cosplayer won a 1995 \"Cash for Photos\" contest held by ''[[Mean Machines Sega]]''.<ref>''Mean Machines Sega'' 31 (May 95), page 6.</ref>|group=\"note\"}}''' the character has been a widely popular subject of [[cosplay]] both in the United States<ref>{{cite news|last=Melendez |first=Elisa |url=http://www.miaminewtimes.com/arts/sexy-miami-geek-girls-pose-for-cosplay-calendar-to-support-animal-shelters-6492911 |title=Sexy Miami Geek Girls Pose for Cosplay Calendar to Support Animal Shelters |newspaper=Miami New Times |date=2013-10-15 |accessdate=2016-01-01}}<br>Heavy Staff, [http://www.heavy.com/games/2012/05/the-hottest-mortal-kombat-cosplay/ The Hottest Mortal Kombat Cosplay], Heavy.com, March 2012.<br>{{cite web|url=http://geektyrant.com/news/2013/9/17/kitana-best-of-cosplay-collection |title=Kitana - Best of Cosplay Collection |publisher=Geektyrant.com |date=2013-09-17 |accessdate=2013-10-15}}<br>{{cite web |url=http://geek-news.mtv.com/2013/08/06/heroes-of-cosplay-cosplayer-reax/ |title=MTV Geek Cosplayers React To NY Post \"Heroes of Cosplay\" Review |publisher=Geek-news.mtv.com |date= |accessdate=2013-12-02 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131013052519/http://geek-news.mtv.com/2013/08/06/heroes-of-cosplay-cosplayer-reax/ |archivedate=2013-10-13 |df= }}<br>{{cite web|url=http://www.ripten.com/2011/07/10/cosplay-spotlight-kitana-mortal-kombat-2011/ |title=Cosplay Spotlight: Kitana (Mortal Kombat) &#124; RipTen Videogame Blog |website=Ripten.com |date=2011-07-10 |accessdate=2016-01-01}}</ref> and abroad,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bild.de/news/ausland/comic/wir-sind-comic-convention-london-41087918.bild.html |title=Die besten Kost\u00fcme bei der Londoner Comic Convention: Wir sind Comic! - News Ausland |language=de |website=Bild.de |date=2015-05-25 |accessdate=2016-01-01}}<br>{{cite web|url=http://www.manga-news.com/index.php/actus/2011/10/22/La-selection-Cosplay-de-la-semaine-avec-Pixidols |title=La s\u00e9lection Cosplay de la semaine avec Pixidols, 22 Octobre 2011 |publisher=Manga news |date= |accessdate=2016-01-01}}<br>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.xgn.nl/de-meest-sexy-cosplay-outfits |title=De meest sexy cosplay outfits |publisher=XGN.nl |date=2015-03-04 |accessdate=2015-05-07}}<br>{{cite web|url=http://guide.supereva.it/cosplay/interventi/2010/02/intervista-ad-adele-brandaglia |title=Intervista ad Adele Brandaglia |website=Guide.supereva.it |date= |accessdate=2016-01-01}}<br>{{cite web|author= |url=http://g1.globo.com/mg/sul-de-minas/noticia/2013/05/de-darth-vader-branca-de-neve-cosplayers-divertem-flipocos.html |title=G1 - De Darth Vader a Branca de Neve: cosplayers divertem a Flipo\u00e7os - not\u00edcias em Sul de Minas |website=G1.globo.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-01}}<br>{{cite web|last=Ino |first=Giovanni |url=http://www.cartoonmag.it/news/emili-fl-umilta-pazienza-e-fisicita-le-armi-di-un-buon-cosplayer.html |title=Emi FL: umilt\u00e0, pazienza e fisicit\u00e0, le armi di un buon cosplayer &#124; Cartoonmag |website=Cartoonmag.it |date=2012-11-25 |accessdate=2016-01-01}}<br>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamesblog.it/post/109549/cosplay-domenicale-nuova-sexy-galleria-primaverile |title=Cosplay domenicale: nuova sexy-galleria primaverile |website=Gamesblog.it |date= |accessdate=2016-01-01}}</ref> particularly among models and entertainers. For instance, Filipina presenter and 2010 ''[[FHM]]'' \"Premiere Vixen\" winner Karen Bordador dressed up as Kitana for a 2011 photo session,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefanboyseo.com/people/karen-bordador-cosplays-as-kitana-from-mortal-kombat|title=Karen Bordador Cosplays as Kitana from Mortal Kombat|date=March 1, 2011|publisher=THE Fanboy SEO|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110602105248/http://www.thefanboyseo.com/people/karen-bordador-cosplays-as-kitana-from-mortal-kombat|archivedate=2011-06-02}}</ref> bodybuilder Tanya Jordan won the Ms. Fitness Southern California 2010 competition by [[Pole dance|pole dancing]] in a Kitana costume,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/body-builder-pole-dances-as-kitana-murders-pedobear|title= Body builder pole dances as Kitana, murders Pedobear|publisher= GamesRadar|first=Tyler|last=Nagata|date=May 21, 2010}}</ref> film maker [[Jen Soska]] dressed as Kitana to fight her sister [[Sylvia Soska|Sylvia]]'s Mileena at [[Fantastic Fest]] 2011,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bloody-mess.net/?p=1074|title=A Candid Interview with The Twisted Twins!|publisher=bloody-mess.net|date=January 10, 2013|accessdate=September 7, 2014}}<br>[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eMNvJLd8BMo Fantastic Fest Fighting Fail, American Mary and Mumblecore] - YouTube, October 11, 2012. Retrieved September 7, 2014.</ref> and dancers from the [[Miami Northwestern Senior High School]] dressed in Kitana for a controversial dance routine in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.eurweb.com/2017/10/high-school-dance-team-under-fire-for-risque-costumes-and-routine/|title=High School Dance Team Under Fire for Risqu\u00e9 Costumes and Routine|last=Report|first=Electronic Urban|date=2017-10-03|work=EURweb|access-date=2018-05-23|language=en-US}}</ref> In the world of martial arts, professional wrestler [[AJ Lee]] (April Jeanette Mendez) dressed as Kitana for the Divas Battle Royal contest in the Halloween 2011 special edition of ''[[WWE Raw|Monday Night Raw]]'', during which she jokingly attempted to perform a \"Fan Lift\" on her opponent,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialplaystationmagazine.co.uk/2011/11/01/wwe-divas-mortal-kombat-kosplay/|title=WWE Diva AJ Lee's Mortal Kombat cosplay|first=Ben|last=Wilson|publisher=Official PlayStation Magazine UK|date=November 1, 2011|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120829091214/http://www.officialplaystationmagazine.co.uk/2011/11/01/wwe-divas-mortal-kombat-kosplay/|archivedate=August 29, 2012|df=}}<br>{{cite web|url=http://www.rpad.tv/2011/11/02/wwe-aj-lee-as-mortal-kombats-kitana-awesome |title=WWE AJ Lee as Mortal Kombat's Kitana=Awesome |first=Raymond |last=Padilla |publisher=RPad.TV |date=November 2, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111205053513/http://www.rpad.tv/2011/11/02/wwe-aj-lee-as-mortal-kombats-kitana-awesome/ |archivedate=December 5, 2011 }}<br>{{cite web|last=Caudill |first=Joshua |url=http://www.craveonline.com/sports/articles/779247-wwe-divas-champion-aj-lee-one-one |title=WWE Divas Champion AJ Lee: One-On-One |publisher=CraveOnline |date=2014-10-24 |accessdate=2016-01-01}}</ref> and mixed-martial artist [[Roxanne Modafferi]] dressed as Kitana for [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]]'s Friday's [[Invicta Fighting Championships|Invicta FC]] 14 official weigh-in in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eventhubs.com/news/2015/sep/14/chun-li-and-kitana-headed-octogon-women-ufc-weigh-dressed-their-favorite-street-fighter-and-mortal-kombat-characters/ |title=Chun-Li and Kitana headed to the Octagon? Women of UFC weigh in dressed as their favorite Street Fighter and Mortal Kombat characters |website=Eventhubs.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-01}}</ref> Other personalities who costumed themselves as the character have included ''[[Maxim (magazine)|Maxim]]'' model Aja Dang at [[San Diego Comic-Con International|ComicCon]] 2012,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maxim.com/comics/100-things-we-saw-comic-con-2012 |title=100 Things We Saw At Comic Con 2012 |author=Gene Newman and Jordan Burchette |publisher=Maxim.com |date=July 18, 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130516214434/http://www.maxim.com/comics/100-things-we-saw-comic-con-2012 |archivedate=May 16, 2013 |df= }}</ref> model [[Jenn Sterger]] in 2013,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://thebiglead.com/2013/10/31/jenn-sterger-dressed-as-kitana-from-mortal-kombat-for-halloween/|title=Jenn Sterger Dressed as Kitana From Mortal Kombat For Halloween|date=2013-10-31|work=The Big Lead|access-date=2018-05-23|language=en-US}}</ref> professional wrestler [[Velvet Sky]] (Jamie Lynn Szantyr) in 2014,<ref>{{cite tweet|user=VelVelHoller|author=\u2728Velvet Sky\u2728|number=395234640576802817|date=29 October 2013|title=@NetherRealm  #MKHalloween #Kitana}}</ref> singer [[Demi Lovato]] in 2017,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://diversao.r7.com/pop/demi-lovato-e-comparada-a-kitana-de-mortal-kombat-29082017|title=Demi Lovato \u00e9 comparada a Kitana, de Mortal Kombat|date=2017-08-29|work=R7.com|access-date=2018-05-23|language=pt-BR}}</ref> and singer and actress [[Teyana Taylor]] in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.w24.co.za/Entertainment/Celebrity-gossip/we-almost-didnt-recognise-our-fave-celebs-in-their-crazy-halloween-costumes-this-past-weekend-20181029|title=We almost didn't recognise our fave celebs in their crazy Halloween costumes this past weekend|website=www.w24.co.za|access-date=2018-11-08}}</ref> In the 2014 sixth season of ''[[RuPaul's Drag Race]],'' contestant [[Adore Delano]] wore a costume of Kitana who she said was her favorite ''Mortal Kombat'' character.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.avclub.com/tvclub/rupauls-drag-race-queens-talk-203451|title=RuPaul's Drag Race: \"Queens Of Talk\" \u00b7 TV Club \u00b7 The A.V. Club|last=Sava|first=Oliver|date=2014-04-15|publisher=Avclub.com|accessdate=2014-05-04}}</ref>\n\n\"Kitana\" has become an occasional [[Neologism|neologistic]] misspelling of the word \"katana.\"{{#tag:ref|Such as in a 2004 [[Associated Press|AP]] article mentioning \"the kitana-blade wielding Mileena\" (additionally confusing the [[katana]] with the [[sai (weapon)|sai]])<ref>Anthony Breznican, [https://web.archive.org/web/20150329042747/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-98802282.html Playboy to Feature Video Game Characters], AP Online, September 8, 2004.</ref> and in a 2012 article by the ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' where the DC Comics character [[Katana (comics)|Katana]] was spelled as \"Kitana.\"<ref>Hero Complex, [http://herocomplex.latimes.com/2012/07/13/comic-con-beware-the-bat-batman/ Comic-Con: After \"TDKR,\" a CG \"Beware the Batman\" will rise], latimes.com, July 13, 2012.</ref>|group=\"note\"}} Though the name itself has no distinct meaning<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.behindthename.com/names/search.php?terms=kitana&type=&x=0&y=0|title=Kitana|publisher=BehindTheName.com|accessdate=February 1, 2015}}</ref> and did not exist before being made-up by Tobias for ''MKII'' in 1993, it is now a given name being in use in the United States and elsewhere.{{#tag:ref|Examples include American soul/punk singer Kitana Andrews,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://rockandrollreport.com/novembers-triple-r-girl-women-who-rock-is-soul-punk-rocker-kitana-andrews/#more-8774|title=November's Triple R Girl Women Who Rock is Soul Punk Rocker Kitana Andrews|author=Allegra|date=November 9, 2009|publisher=The Rock & Roll Report|accessdate=February 2, 2015}}</ref> American actress Kitana Turnbull,<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2018/film/features/cannes-netflix-buys-animated-robot-movie-next-gen-for-30-million-worldwide-deal-1202807343/|title=Cannes: Netflix Buys Animated Robot Movie \u2018Next Gen\u2019 for $30 Million Worldwide Deal|first=Ramin|last=Setoodeh|date=11 May 2018|magazine=Variety}}</ref> American basketball player Kitana High,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newalbanygazette.com/content/player-week-kitana-high|title=Player of the Week: Kitana High|last=Zaremba|first=Elizabeth|date=2012-11-01|publisher=NewAlbanyGazette.com|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203092203/http://www.newalbanygazette.com/content/player-week-kitana-high|archivedate=December 3, 2013|url-status=dead|accessdate=2013-12-01}}</ref> and British amateur golfer Kitana Hollins.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenorthernecho.co.uk/sport/10838217.Golf_shorts__Kitana_enjoys_successful_2013/|title=Golf shorts: Kitana Hollins enjoys successful 2013|last=Fraser|first=Paul|date=|publisher=Thenorthernecho.co.uk|accessdate=2013-12-01}}</ref>|group=\"note\"}} \"Kitana Jade\" has been the alias of American adult model [[Cherie Roberts]] since 1999, [[Kitana Baker]] is the adopted name of an American model born Christi Josenhans, and [[Kitana Kiki Rodriguez]] is a name taken by an American transgender actress. It is also the name of the main character in [[Derek Landy]]'s 2012 novel ''[[Skulduggery Pleasant: Kingdom of the Wicked]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2014/apr/18/review-derek-landy-kingdom-wicked-skulduggery-pleasant|title=Skulduggery Pleasant: Kingdom of the Wicked by Derek Landy - review|date=April 18, 2014|newspaper=The Guardian|accessdate=September 7, 2014}}</ref> {{clear}}\n\n== Reception ==\n===Critical reactions and popularity===\nCritical reception of Kitana has been mostly very positive, often with emphasis placed on her good looks and sometimes on her relatively complicated personality. She has become commonly regarded to be one of the most recognizable characters of the ''Mortal Kombat'' franchise. ''Mortal Kombat II'' was described by ''[[CU Amiga]]'' as \"Kitana & Co\" and by ''GamePro'' as \"Kitana and crew\"<ref>\"Shadow Fighter\", CU Amiga 62 (April 95), page 56.</ref><ref>Slasher Quan, ''GamePro'' issue 63 (October 1994), page 41.</ref> and ''Total 64'' called Kitana the \"babe\" of ''Mortal Kombat Trilogy'', saying that her gameplay problems \"all can be forgiven when we look at those legs.\"<ref name=total>''Total 64'' 2/97, page 58.</ref> Criticizing characters of the game ''[[War Gods (video game)|War Gods]]''[[War Gods (video game)|,]] made by the same team as ''Mortal Kombat'', ''[[Computer and Video Games]]'' used Kitana as an example of a contrasting \"awesome\" character.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=June 1996|title=News: War Gods|url=|journal=CVG|volume=174|pages=12|via=}}</ref> According to [[Tom's Hardware]] in 2007, \"Kitana is arguably the best known and most popular woman in the ''Mortal Kombat'' series.\"<ref name=tom/> She placed fourth on the 2005 list of top \"old school\" ''Mortal Kombat'' characters by [[Game Revolution]]'s Anthony Severino,<ref name=\"OldschoolMK\"/> ranked as the fifth top character in the series by Robert Workman of GamePlayBook in 2010,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gameplaybook.com/news/the-best-mortal-kombat-characters-of-all-time/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100820010338/http://www.gameplaybook.com/news/the-best-mortal-kombat-characters-of-all-time/|archivedate=2010-08-20|title=The Best Mortal Kombat Characters of All Time |author=Robert Workman |publisher=GamePlayBook |date=August 9, 2010 |accessdate=2011-12-27}}</ref> and was voted the ninth top Mortal Kombat fighter by the staff of [[UGO Networks|UGO]] in 2012.<ref name=ugo>{{cite web|author=UGO Team |url=http://www.ugo.com/games/mortal-kombat-characters?page=5 |title=Top 50 Mortal Kombat Characters - Mortal Kombat |publisher=UGO.com |date=2012-02-28 |accessdate=2012-03-04 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120929141958/http://www.ugo.com/games/mortal-kombat-characters?page=5 |archivedate=2012-09-29 |df= }}</ref> Fans voted Kitana the series' twelfth-greatest character in a 2013 fan-voted poll by [[CollegeHumor|Dorkly]] that rated the entire ''Mortal Kombat'' roster.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dorkly.com/toplist/56586/the-greatest-mortal-kombat-character-of-all-time |title=The Greatest Mortal Kombat Character of All-Time (Vote Now!) - Dorkly Toplist |publisher=Dorkly.com |date= |accessdate=2013-12-19}}</ref> Mixed martial artist [[Ronda Rousey]] named Kitana as her favourite ''Mortal Kombat'' character.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamerant.com/ronda-rousey-pokemon-reddit-312/|title=Ronda Rousey Talks Pokemon, Mortal Kombat, & World of Warcraft on Reddit|date=|website=Gamerant.com|accessdate=2016-01-01}}</ref> Actresses [[Natalie Martinez]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.esquire.com/entertainment/news/a36311/natalie-martinez-self-less-interview/|title=Natalie Martinez Pics - Natalie Martinez on Mortal Kombat, Muy Thai, Self/Less|last=Editors|first=Esquire|date=2015-07-10|website=Esquire.com|accessdate=2016-01-01}}</ref> and [[Megan Fox]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://cinepop.com.br/exclusivo-megan-fox-quer-interpretar-kitana-no-remake-de-mortal-kombat-119877|title=EXCLUSIVO: Megan Fox quer interpretar Kitana no remake de 'Mortal Kombat' {{!}} CinePOP|last=Marafon|first=Renato|website=cinepop.com.br|language=pt-BR|access-date=2018-05-23}}</ref> both said that their dream role would be to play Kitana in a movie.\n\nAt the time of her introduction, ''[[Times Union (Albany)|Times Union]]'' described Kitana as \"the sexy and vicious fighter\" and \"a killer babe who melds a mix of seduction and violence.\"<ref>''Times Union'', January 30, 1994.</ref> According to ''[[Amiga Format]]'' in 1994, while it might be \"incredibly sad for adult males to fancy in game female characters,\" one should be \"prepared to fall in love\" with Kitana.<ref>''Amiga Format'' 66 (December 1994), page 47.</ref> The ''[[Austin American-Statesman]]'' described Kitana and Mileena as \"far nastier than that martial-artless aerobics instructor from the [[Mortal Kombat (1992 video game)|first game]].\"<ref>''Austin American-Statesman'', September 8, 1994.</ref> According to Joey Esposito of [[MTV]], \"it's obvious that ''Mortal Kombat II'' added in some more, let\u2019s say, [[Sexual suggestiveness|sexually suggestive]] characters in Mileena and Kitana.\"<ref name=\"mtv\">{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/2132456/mortal-kombat-fatalities/ |title=9 'Mortal Kombat' Fatalities That Warped Your Childhood |publisher=MTV.com |date=2015-04-13 |accessdate=2015-07-01}}</ref> One of the many false rumors surrounding the game at the time concerned a supposed \"Nudality\" (or \"Sexuality\") finishing move that would be performed by Kitana stripping naked.<ref>Dan Elektro, [https://web.archive.org/web/20110607100041/http://www.gamepro.com/article/features/30667/secrets-lies-page-2/ \"Secrets & Lies\"], GamePro, August 07, 2003.</ref> Years later, in 2004, ''[[Vibe (magazine)|Vibe's]]'' Stud Houston admitted he had a crush on Kitana, describing her as \"sexy as hell,\"<ref>Stud Houston, \"Virtual Sex\", ''Vibe'', December 2004 (p.197).</ref> and MTV Multiplayer's Kendra Beltran chose Kitana as the number one female character on her 2013 list of \"video game crushes you had as a kid\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://multiplayerblog.mtv.com/2013/05/15/top-10-video-game-loves/ |title=Top 10 Video Game Crushes You Had As A Kid |publisher=Multiplayerblog.mtv.com |date=2013-05-15 |accessdate=2014-01-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140115050807/http://multiplayerblog.mtv.com/2013/05/15/top-10-video-game-loves/ |archivedate=2014-01-15 |df= }}</ref> The relationship between the \"smoking hot\" Kitana and Liu Kang was ranked as the fourth best video game couple by the staff of IGN in 2006.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://ps2.ign.com/articles/688/688837p1.html| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110629123257/http://ps2.ign.com/articles/688/688837p1.html| archivedate = 2011-06-29| title = Top 10 Tuesday: Best Videogame Romances| website = IGN|date=February 14, 2006| accessdate = July 18, 2010}}</ref> Rob Wright of [[Tom's Hardware|Tom's Games]] included this \"enduring and powerful character\" on his 2007 list of the 50 greatest female characters in video game history for being a \"powerful princess that's lived more than 10,000 years and still hasn't lost her hotness,\"<ref name=tom>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080325101953/http://www.tomsgames.com/us/2007/02/20/the_50_greatest_female_characters_in_the_history_of_video_games/page13.html \"The 50 Greatest Female Characters in Video Game History\"], Tom's Games, 2007-02-20.</ref> ''[[X-One|X360]]'' featured her on the list of \"an alternative top ten females in gaming\" in 2009,<ref name=x360/> and James Hawkins of [[Joystick Division]] ranked her as the fifth top \"badass lady\" in video games in 2010.<ref>James Hawkins, [http://www.joystickdivision.com/2010/05/the_top_ten_badass_ladies_in_v.php?page=2 The Top Ten Badass Ladies in Video Game History] {{Webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130216081230/http://www.joystickdivision.com/2010/05/the_top_ten_badass_ladies_in_v.php?page=2 |date=2013-02-16 }}, Joystick Division, May 20, 2010.</ref> VideoGamer.com's Wesley Yin-Poole included Princess Kitana on his 2010 list of top ten \"video game crushes\" as rivaling [[Princess Peach]] for number one video game monarch and winning out \"in sheer [[sex appeal]].\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.videogamer.com/features/article/top_10_video_game_crushes.html?page=7|title=Top 10 Video Game Crushes: The female game characters who waggled our joysticks|publisher=VideoGamer.com |author=Yin-Poole, Wesley|date=March 30, 2010|accessdate=September 7, 2011}}</ref> Danny Gallagher of MTV's Guy Code ranked Kitana as the fourth \"best babe in video games\" of 2011, stating that she not only has \"a great pair of long legs\" but also \"the deepest emotional core of any of the ''Mortal Kombat'' characters.\"<ref>Danny Gallagher, [http://guycodeblog.mtv.com/2011/12/06/best-video-game-babes-of-2011/ Best Babes In Video Games Of 2011], MTV Guy Code Blog, 12/6/11.</ref> In 2014, [[WatchMojo.com]] ranked Kitana as the third top female fighting game character,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.watchmojo.com/video/id/12702 |title=Top 10 Female Fighting Game Characters |publisher=WatchMojo.com |date= |accessdate=2015-07-01}}</ref> while WhatCulture ranked her as the 16th greatest character of the fighting game genre in 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whatculture.com/gaming/20-greatest-ever-beat-em-video-game-characters.php/6 |title=20 Greatest Ever Beat Em Up Video Game Characters \u00bb Page 6 of 21 |publisher=Whatculture.com |date= |accessdate=2014-01-17}}</ref> furthermore placing her tenth and fifth in their 2015 rankings of ''Mortal Kombat'' characters and female fighting game characters, respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://whatculture.com/gallery/20-greatest-mortal-kombat-characters-of-all-time/12|title=20 Greatest ''Mortal Kombat'' Characters of All Time|first=Joe|last=Pring|publisher=WhatCulture.com|date=April 2015|accessdate=April 29, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://whatculture.com/gallery/30-greatest-female-fighting-game-characters-of-all-time/27 |title=30 Greatest Female Fighting Game Characters Of All Time - Page 27 |website=Whatculture.com |date=2015-05-21 |accessdate=2016-01-01}}</ref> [[Game Revolution|GameRevolution]] included Kitana in their list of ten best female characters in 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gamerevolution.com/features/12824-10-best-female-video-game-characters|title=10 Best Female Video Game Characters - GameRevolution|date=2016-08-29|work=GameRevolution|access-date=2018-05-23|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n====Sex appeal====\nKitana has quickly become one of the ''Mortal Kombat'' series' [[sex symbol]]s, in a display of what one author described as manifestation of \"pseudo-Japanese [[Orient]]alist [[Sexual fetishism|fetishes]].\"<ref>Sheng-Mei Ma, ''The Deathly Embrace: Orientalism and Asian American Identity'', University of Minnesota Press, 2000 (p.72)</ref> She has been featured in many lists of all gaming's most attractive female characters by various foreign publications, including as one of the 20 \"[[muse]]s\" of video games by Brazilian magazine ''SuperGamePower'' in 2001,<ref>{{cite journal |date=April 2001 |title=As Musas Do Videogame |trans-title=The Muses of Videogames |url=https://archive.org/stream/SuperGamePower_Ano_07_No._085_2001-04_Nova_Cultural_BR_pt#page/n11/mode/2up |journal=SuperGamePower |issue=85 |page=13 |language=Portuguese }}</ref> one of the nine \"sexiest babes of [[action game]]s\" by ''[[The Times of India]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tech/itslideshow/4344370.cms |title=Princess Kitana, Mortal Kombat |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com|accessdate=2014-01-17}}</ref> and one of the 21 \"sexy ladies of computer games\" by Poland's ''[[Fakt]]'' in 2009.<ref>[http://www.fakt.pl/Seksowne-panie-w-grach-komputerowych,galeria,1056,16.html \"Zamaskowana Kitana pojawia si\u0119 w bijatyce \"Mortal Kombat\" - Seksowne panie w grach komputerowych\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316082901/http://www.fakt.pl/Seksowne-panie-w-grach-komputerowych,galeria,1056,16.html |date=2012-03-16 }}, ''Fakt'', 2009-11-13.</ref> In 2008, [[GameDaily]] ranked her as the 28th top \"hottest game babe\", noting her as \"the most worthy of the ''Mortal Kombat II'' babes,\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/galleries/top-25-hottest-game-babes/?page=25 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080915171826/http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/galleries/top-25-hottest-game-babes/?page=25 |archivedate=2008-09-15 |title=Top 50 Hottest Game Babes on Trial |publisher=Web.archive.org |date=2008-09-15 |accessdate=2014-01-17}}</ref> while UGO similarly ranked her as the 28th top \"videogame hottie\",<ref>[http://www.ugo.com/games/video-game-hotties-kitana \"Top 50 Videogame Hotties\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415043142/http://www.ugo.com/games/video-game-hotties-kitana |date=2012-04-15 }}. UGO.com. Retrieved on 2008-12-14.</ref> and [[GamesRadar]] featured her on the list of top 20 supposedly overlooked \"game babes\".<ref>[https://www.gamesradar.com/top-20-overlooked-game-babes/ \"Top 20 Overlooked Game Babes | The Sexy Ladies of B Squad bring their A-game and D-cups\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121003072304/http://www.gamesradar.com/top-20-overlooked-game-babes/ |date=2012-10-03 }}, GamesRadar, July 8, 2008.</ref> In 2009, ''Complex'' featured her as one of top ten \"hottest video game girls\", calling her \"the sexiest [[Cougar (slang)|cougar]] ever.\"<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20121227082946/http://www.complex.com/girls/2009/02/the-10-hottest-video-game-girls \"The 10 Hottest Video Game Girls\"], ''Complex'', March 2, 2009.</ref> In 2011, Anurag Ghosh and Bill Fulks at Bright Hub named \"the gorgeous Kitana\" as the sexiest ''Mortal Kombat'' character,<ref>Anurag Ghosh, Bill Fulks, [http://www.brighthub.com/video-games/pc/articles/126073.aspx#secn_4 Ten Awesome Mortal Kombat Characters: Mileena] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111229211722/http://www.brighthub.com/video-games/pc/articles/126073.aspx#secn_4 |date=2011-12-29 }}, Bright Hub, October 27, 2011.</ref> while [[GameFront]]'s Ross Lincoln ranked her bust in the new game as the 30th-finest in gaming history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamefront.com/the-greatest-boobs-in-video-game-history-gallery/ |title=The Greatest Boobs In Video Game History |publisher=GameFront |date= May 5, 2011 |author=Ross Lincoln}}</ref> In 2012, Kitana was declared the second-sexiest character in video games by Fernando DaQuino of TecMundo, who noted her being \"well far from a princess stereotype,\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tecmundo.com.br/selecao/33744-as-10-personagens-mais-sexy-dos-video-games.htm |title=As 10 personagens mais sexy dos video games |publisher=Tecmundo.com.br |date= December 7, 2012 |accessdate=2014-03-02 |language=Portuguese}}</ref> and included among the 20 \"hottest women\" in video game history by [[MSN]] Malaysia.<ref>[http://tech.malaysia.msn.com/photoviewer.aspx?cp-documentid=250764311 The hottest women in video game history] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130228110539/http://tech.malaysia.msn.com/photoviewer.aspx?cp-documentid=250764311 |date=2013-02-28 }}, MSN, 21 September 2012.</ref> UGO ranked her as the \"38th-hottest fictional woman\" of the year, commenting that the ''Mortal Kombat'' series \"has always boasted some hotties, but the new game brought back Kitana in a big way.\"<ref>[http://www.ugo.com/games/video-game-hotties-kitana \"The 99 Hottest Fictional Women Of 2012\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415043142/http://www.ugo.com/games/video-game-hotties-kitana |date=2012-04-15 }}, UGO.com, February 1, 2012.</ref> Kitana was rated as the seventh-sexiest \"video game girl\" by Nixie Pixel of [[Revision3]],<ref>Nixie Pixel (Nicole Allen), [http://revision3.com/nixiepixel/hot-game-girls The 7 Sexiest Video Game Girls] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021044728/http://revision3.com/nixiepixel/hot-game-girls |date=2013-10-21 }}, Revision3, September 27th, 2012.</ref> and Jo\u00e3o Vitor de Oliveira from Brazilian edition of ''[[Official Xbox Magazine]]'' placed her fifth on his list of sexiest women in fighting games.<ref>Jo\u00e3o Vitor de Oliveira, \"Ranking: As lutadoras mais gatas\". ''Revista Oficial No Xbox'' 12/2013, page 88.</ref> In 2013, Kitana was also ranked as the fifth-sexiest female video game character of all time by AMOG's Albert Costill, who referred to her as \"not only one of the most recognizable characters from ''Mortal Kombat'',\" but \"also one of the coolest, and definitely sexiest,\"<ref>{{cite web |last=Costill |first=Albert |url=http://amog.com/babes/156918-10-sexiest-female-video-game-characters-time/ |title=The 10 Sexiest Female Video Game Characters of All Time |publisher=AMOG |date= |accessdate=2013-06-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130608123132/http://amog.com/babes/156918-10-sexiest-female-video-game-characters-time/ |archivedate=2013-06-08 |df= }}</ref> as well as the second-sexiest female video game character by Scarlet Clearwater of [[Soletron]].<ref>Scarlet Clearwater, [http://soletron.com/the-10-hottest-female-video-game-characters/ The 10 Hottest Female Video Game Characters] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130618070823/http://soletron.com/the-10-hottest-female-video-game-characters/ |date=2013-06-18 }}, Soletron, June 13, 2013.</ref> Kitana was ranked as the 56th-best-looking game woman by Brazilian site [[GameHall]]'s Portal PlayGame in 2014, with a comment that since her first appearance she \"has stirred imagination of ''MK'' players and gained fans around the world.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://portalplaygame.com/top-100-as-personagens-mais-gatas-dos-games/ |title=TOP 100\u2014As Personagens mais gatas dos games |publisher=GameHall |language=Portuguese |date=2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123234148/http://portalplaygame.com/top-100-as-personagens-mais-gatas-dos-games/ |archivedate=2015-01-23 |df= }}</ref> In 2015, Indonesian television station [[Liputan 6]] ranked her as the eighth-sexiest Oriental woman character in video games.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tekno.liputan6.com/read/2177958/10-karakter-game-wanita-oriental-yang-cantik-nan-seksi?p=8|title=10 Karakter Game Wanita Oriental yang Cantik nan Seksi|author=Jeko Iqbal Reza|publisher=liputan6.com|language=tr}}</ref> Kitana has been one of the most searched video games on [[Pornhub]] in 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gonintendo.com/stories/299310-pornhub-reveals-top-game-character-searches-of-2017-pokemon-and|title=Pornhub reveals top game character searches of 2017, Pokemon and Zelda make the list|work=GoNintendo|access-date=2018-05-23|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Sonya vs Kitana Dragon Con 2012.jpg|thumb|250px|Cosplayers of [[Sonya Blade]] and Kitana (''Mortal Kombat II'' classic costume) at [[Dragon*Con]] 2012. Game designer [[David Jaffe]] has described Sonya and Kitana as \"two of the hottest chix in gaming.\"<ref name=jaffe/>]]\n\nShe has drawn comparisons to the series' first female character, Sonya Blade. Kitana tied for eighth with Sonya in ''Complex's'' 2010 list of the \"hottest women in video games.\"<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20111108122226/http://www.complex.com/video-games/2010/11/the-50-hottest-women-in-video-games/ \"The 50 Hottest Women In Video Games\"], ''Complex'', November 8, 2010.</ref> In 2010, during development of the ''Mortal Kombat'' reboot, ''[[God of War (franchise)|God of War]]'' series director [[David Jaffe]] explicitly wrote how his character [[Kratos (God of War)|Kratos]] would have \"a FUCKALITY\" with \"Sonya AND {{sic|Katana}}\"{{#tag:ref|\"Katana\" is a fairly-common misspelling of Kitana's name and Kratos was indeed soon added to the [[List of Mortal Kombat characters|''Mortal Kombat'' games' character roster]] in ''MK2011''.|group=\"note\"}} if he joined the series<ref>[http://kotaku.com/5709627/video-game-creators-invent-the-darndest-finishing-moves \"Video Game Creators Invent The Darndest Finishing Moves\"], Kotaku, December 8, 2010.</ref> (Jaffe later explained that he does not advocate rape, as it was interpreted by some, and that his comment was to suggest that Kratos would \"get a [[threesome]]\" as a reward<ref name=jaffe>Robert Purchese, [http://www.eurogamer.net/articles/2010-12-09-jaffe-kratos-shouldnt-rape-mk-victims \"Jaffe: Kratos shouldn't rape MK victims\"], Eurogamer.net, 9/12/2010.</ref>). In 2012, Kitana was ranked as the second-top \"hottest\" female video game character by Kristie Bertucci of ''Gadget Review,'' who called her \"way hotter\" than Sonya.<ref>Kristie Bertucci, [http://www.gadgetreview.com/2012/07/20-hottest-female-video-game-characters.html 20 hottest female video game characters (list)], Gadget Review, 5 July 2012.</ref> That same year, [[JoBlo.com]] placed Kitana ninth on their list of the ten \"hottest video game characters,\" likewise stating that Sonya \"had nothing on her\" and calling her a \"videogame babe for the ages,\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.joblo.com/hollywood-celebrities/gossip/lists-the-sexy-ten-spot-hottest-video-game-characters/item#9 |title=The Sexy Ten Spot: Hottest Videogame Characters |publisher=Joblo.com |date=2012-10-31 |accessdate=2014-01-17}}</ref> while UGO suggested that Kitana and her mother Sindel should be on every \"hot females in videogames\" list.<ref name=\"ugo\"/> Kitana and Mileena were included among the \"old-school hotties that still got it\" by Travis Hubert of Cheat Code Central in 2014, who stated that \"these two have become synonymous with the sex appeal of the ''Mortal Kombat'' series [and] even surpassed the popularity of Sonya Blade, who was the original ''MK'' hottie.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://lists.cheatcc.com/190?page=3 | title=10 Old School Hotties That Still Got It | date=May 7, 2014 | author=Huber, Travis | publisher=Cheat Code Central | accessdate=May 14, 2014}}</ref> Placing her 19th in their 2015 ranking of the series' 73 playable characters, [[Dennis Publishing|Den of Geek]] opined \"Kitana became one of the breakout stars of the series, easily having more meat on her character than Sonya ever did.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.denofgeek.us/games/mortal-kombat/243041/mortal-kombat-ranking-all-the-characters/page/0/4|title=Mortal Kombat: Ranking All the Characters|first=Gavin|last=Jasper|publisher=Den of Geek|date=January 30, 2015|accessdate=February 3, 2015}}</ref>\n\nKitana has also often shared the media spotlight with Mileena and Jade; GameFront's Phil Owen considered them all \"basically the same character.\"<ref>Phil Owen, [http://www.gamefront.com/mortal-kombat-the-very-bestworst-jade-mileena-kitana-cosplay-pics/ Mortal Kombat: The Very Best/Worst Jade, Mileena & Kitana Cosplay (PICS)], GameFront, April 18, 2011.</ref> At the time of the release of ''MKII'', ''[[The Miami Herald]]'' called Kitana and Mileena (\"leggy ladies who wear masks\") to be \"an interesting step toward [[political correctness]]\" as \"a far cry from [[Little Miss Muffet]]\".<ref>''Miami Herald'', August 26, 1994.</ref> Brazilian magazine ''A\u00e7\u00e3o Games'' placed her and Mileena at the eight spot on their list of \"Top Girls\" in 1997.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Montoia|first=Paulo|date=April 1997|title=Lindas Gatas Invadem os Games|url=|journal=A\u00e7\u00e3o Games|volume=114|pages=22\u201323|via=}}</ref> In a retrospective article from 2011, IGN's Richard George listed \"the hot chicks\" as one of the reasons why ''Mortal Kombat II'' \"is considered by many to be the pinnacle of the series.\"<ref>Richard George, [https://uk.ign.com/top/snes-games/25 Mortal Kombat II - #25 Top 100 SNES Games], IGN, 2011.</ref> Alongside Mileena and Jade, Kitana was included on the list of the \"hottest chicks of 2011\" by [[Univision]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://videojuegos.univision.com/noticias/slideshow/2011-12-29/chicas-mas-candentes-2011 |accessdate=January 1, 2016 |title=Las chicas m\u00e1s candentes de 2011|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150910082720/http://videojuegos.univision.com/noticias/slideshow/2011-12-29/chicas-mas-candentes-2011 |archivedate=September 10, 2015 }}</ref> The three of them all shared a spot on the 2014 list of top ten \"hottest\" female villains in gaming by Cheat Code Central's Travis Huber.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://lists.cheatcc.com/138?page=3 |title=Top 10 Hottest Female Villains in Gaming |publisher=Cheat Code Central |date= |accessdate=2014-01-13}}</ref> In 2009, ''GamePro''{{'}}s Aaron Koehn ranked Mileena and Kitana as the 11th-best pair of palette-swapped video game characters, writing that \"both prefer wearing clothing that shows off their inflated mammary glands, and both have used the usually endearing gesture of kissing as a fatality.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.gamepro.com/article/features/208570/17-best-palette-swapped-characters/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100807173901/http://www.gamepro.com/article/features/208570/17-best-palette-swapped-characters |archivedate=August 7, 2010 |first=Aaron|last=Koehn|title=Palette Swapping: 17 Games that Did it Right|magazine= GamePro|date=January 13, 2009}}</ref> The two were featured in GamesRadar's 2006 list of top seven \"girls kissing girls,\"<ref name=kiss>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamesradar.com/the-top-7-girl-on-girl-kisses |first=Mikel |last=Reparaz |publisher=GamesRadar |title=The Top 7... Girl-on-girl kisses |date=November 28, 2006 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121002234020/http://www.gamesradar.com/the-top-7-girl-on-girl-kisses/ |archivedate=October 2, 2012 |df= }}</ref> and \"Kitana's and Mileena's deadly kisses\" were chosen as the favourite Fatalities by [[RetroGamer]]'s Paul Drury in 2007.<ref>\"The Retrobates: Best Mortal Kombat Fatality\" in ''Retro Gamer'' 40.</ref> Lauren Alessandra of GamingUnion.net wrote that Kitana \"easily fits in\" the number six spot on her 2011 list of top video game heroines, stating that \"her and her 'clone' sister for that matter quickly became poster girls for the series.\"<ref>Lauren Alessandra, [http://www.gamingunion.net/news/top-10-video-game-heroines--5814.html Top 10 Video Game Heroines] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131015114743/http://www.gamingunion.net/news/top-10-video-game-heroines--5814.html |date=2013-10-15 }}, GamingUnion.net, July 17th, 2011.</ref> In 2012, UGO similarly described \"the busty ninja sisters Kitana and Mileena\" as the front characters of the ''Mortal Kombat'' franchise.<ref>[http://www.ugo.com/movies/best-movie-ever-mortal-kombat-kano-vs-sonya-blade Kano Vs. Sonya Blade] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.today/20130105031449/http://www.ugo.com/movies/best-movie-ever-mortal-kombat-kano-vs-sonya-blade |date=2013-01-05 }}, UGO, February 23, 2012.</ref> Kitana was voted at second place in the ''Mortal Kombat'' category of \"Miss of Video Games 2012\" by Polish magazine ''PSX Extreme'', where she ultimately lost to Jade.<ref>Roger \u017bochowski, [http://www.ppe.pl/news-8890-Miss_Gier_Wideo_Mortal_Kombat.html Miss Gier Wideo: Mortal Kombat], PPE.PL, 2011-07-16.<br>Roger \u017bochowski, [http://www.ppe.pl/news-9072-Miss_Gier_Wideo_Soul_Calibur.html Miss Gier Wideo: Soul Calibur], PPE.PL, 2011-07-30.</ref> In 2014, Jade and Kitana together placed ninth on the sexiest female video game characters list by WatchMojo.com,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=2Gx5Bx6PE9A|title=Top 10 Sexiest Female Video Game Characters|publisher=WatchMojo.com via YouTube|date=July 14, 2014|accessdate=September 7, 2014}}</ref> while Zoomin.TV ranked Kitana second among their 2015 \"top five sexiest ''Mortal Kombat'' girls\" which also included Jade as well as Skarlet.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9Za618QcMaY |title=Top 5 - Sexiest Mortal Kombat girls |publisher=YouTube.com |date=2015-04-13 |accessdate=2015-07-01}}</ref> ''Playboy'' included Mileena, Kitana, and Jade together among \"the hottest video game breasts of all time\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.playboy.com/galleries/hottest-video-game-breasts/slide-25|title=2-Up: The Hottest Video Game Breasts of All Time - Slide 25|last=|first=|date=2016-03-29|website=Playboy|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160329130259/http://www.playboy.com/galleries/hottest-video-game-breasts/slide-25|archive-date=2016-03-29|url-status=dead|access-date=2018-05-24}}</ref>\n\nKitana was listed among the 25 \"hottest (and deadliest) ninja assassin chicks\" in all media by UGO in 2011 for having \"brains and brawn, not to mention a wardrobe full of sparse clothing.\"<ref>[http://www.ugo.com/girls/hot-ninja-girls?page=5 \"Ninja Chicks are So Freakin' Hot\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110615162936/http://www.ugo.com/girls/hot-ninja-girls?page=5 |date=2011-06-15 }}, UGO.com, January 5, 2011.</ref> ''Complex'' editors pitted the \"as deadly as she is beautiful\" Kitana against [[Taki (Soulcalibur)|Taki]] from the ''[[Soul (series)|Soulcalibur]]'' series for the 2011 \"battle of the beauties\" in the category \"female ninjas\", which resulted in a draw between the two,<ref>Rich Knight, [http://www.complex.com/video-games/2011/11/battle-of-the-beauties-gamings-hottest-female-characters-face-off#9 Battle of the Beauties: Gaming's Hottest Female Characters Face Off], Complex.com, November 9, 2011.</ref> and ranked Kitana as the tenth-top female killer from video games in 2012, noting that \"she is still holding down her spot on the hot female assassins list\" nearly two decades after her debut.<ref>[http://www.complex.com/video-games/2012/06/promo-10-hot-female-killers-from-video-games#1 10 Hot Female Killers From Video Games], Complex.com, June 6, 2012.</ref> Gelo Gonzales of ''FHM'' listed Kitana as one the nine \"sexiest ninja babes in games\" in 2012, comparing her to [[Eula Valdez]].<ref>Gelo Gonzales, [http://www.fhm.com.ph/entertainment/games/article/12024# 9 Sexiest Ninja Babes in Games] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120401005026/http://www.fhm.com.ph/entertainment/games/article/12024 |date=2012-04-01 }}, ''FHM'', March 29, 2012.</ref> M\u00e1rcio Pacheco Alexsandro of GameHall placed Kitana and Mileena at second spot of his 2014 list of top ten female ninja characters in games.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gamehall.uol.com.br/v10/top-10-kunoichis-ninjas-femininas-dos-games/ |title=Top 10 Kunoichis (Ninjas Femininas) dos Games \u00ab GameHall Network |publisher=Gamehall.uol.com.br |date= |accessdate=2014-04-12 |language=pt |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140415021848/http://gamehall.uol.com.br/v10/top-10-kunoichis-ninjas-femininas-dos-games/ |archive-date=2014-04-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 2017, GameRant ranked her as the fifth best ninja character of ''Mortal Komba''t, stating she should be just \"written off as 'Mileena Lite'\" and calling her fans the perhaps most iconic weapon in the series.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://screenrant.com/mortal-kombat-every-ninja-ranked-worst-best/|title=Mortal Kombat: Every Ninja Ranked From Worst To Best|date=2017-10-06|work=ScreenRant|access-date=2018-05-23|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n====Gender criticism and Fatalities====\n{{quote box|quote=Q: [[Gender representation in video games|Gender in video games]] has become the new hotbed of critical discussion. Kitana and Sonya remain two of the strongest and earliest female leads in gaming. How did they come about and do you see them as a vital legacy for the series? <br> A: Sure, they were both important pieces of the game's fiction and [[archetype|archetypal]] structure of characters. But, our player demographic was primarily a hardcore male audience and so the look and design of our female characters pandered to them back then just as they do today. I have no problem being apologetic for that. The only solace I can offer is that both of those characters had very strong, atypical female archetypes... and at the very least could kick the hell out of their male counterparts.|source=\u2014[[John Tobias]] for Mortal Kombat Online in 2012<ref>[http://www.mortalkombatonline.com/content/News/read.cds?article=1725 In Konversation: Mortal Kombat Online vs John Tobias - Part 1], Mortal Kombat Online, 09/17/2012.</ref>|width=30%}}\n\nThere have been controversies and mixed or negative critical reception of the character. In 1994, she was one of the fighting game characters cited by [[Guy Aoki]] of ''[[AsianWeek]]'' as allegedly perpetuating existing [[Stereotypes of East Asians in the United States|stereotypes of Asians]] as martial arts experts.<ref>Aoki, Guy. \"Do Fighting Video Games Prolong Stereotypes of Asian Americans?\", ''AsianWeek'', September 23, 1994.</ref> In the [[Video game controversies|video game violence controversy]] themed book ''Interacting With Video'', Patricia Marks Greenfield and Rodney R. Cocking used the \"two Asian twin sisters, Kitana and Mileena\" as an example of \"highly eroticized [[Dragon Lady]]\" stereotyping in video games.<ref>Patricia Marks Greenfield, Rodney R. Cocking, ''Interacting With Video'' (p.34).</ref> When [[Marsha Kinder]] accused ''Mortal Kombat II'' of [[misogyny]] in its handling of female characters, she alleged that \"some of the most violent possibilities are against women,\" whose own \"fatality moves are highly eroticised.\"<ref>\"Women, of a sort, enter Mortal Kombat\", ''Milwaukee Journal Sentinel'', May 29, 1995.</ref> Patrick Sunnen's book ''Making Sense of Video Games'' judged their portrayal as \"formidable female opponents\" to be potentially progressive, yet arguably made just to increase \"the [[Sexism|sexist]] potential of the individual fights\", and described Kitana's Fatality of decapitation with a \"deceptively feminine razor-sharp fan\" to be [[castration]]-like.<ref>Patrick Sunnen, ''Making Sense of Video Games'', University of London (p.19).</ref> Chad Hunter of ''Complex'' chose Jade and Kitana to represent the \"women who fight\" stereotype in his 2012 list of the fifteen most stereotypical characters in video games, for being \"half-naked skanks who can fight, hurl lasers and perform aerobatic attacks while wearing thongs, high-heeled boots and keeping their giant breasts under scarves,\" claiming that this has caused \"female gamers [to] slide away from this series.\"<ref>Chad Hunter, [http://www.complex.com/video-games/2012/05/the-15-most-stereotypical-characters-in-video-games/jade-kitana-mortal-kombat The 15 Most Stereotypical Characters In Video Games], Complex.com, May 9, 2010.</ref> In a satire article \"''Mortal Kombat II'' warriors: Where are they now?\" by [[VentureBeat]]'s Jason Lomberg, Kitana \"joined the [[National Organization for Women]] and started an online campaign to recognize and combat the rampant [[sexual harassment]] in organized death tournaments. [[Mai Shiranui]], [[Cammy]], [[Morrigan Aensland|Morrigan]], and Mileena all stepped forward to share their stories.\"<ref>Jason Lomberg, [https://venturebeat.com/2012/05/13/mortal-kombat-ii-warriors-where-are-they-now/ Mortal Kombat II warriors: Where are they now?], VentureBeat, May 13, 2012.</ref>\n\nKitana's finishing moves have been critically received variably but mostly positively, especially in regards to her famous signature \"Kiss of Death\".<ref name=kiss/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.techtudo.com.br/listas/noticia/2015/03/mortal-kombat-relembre-os-fatalities-classicos-da-serie-de-luta.html |title=Mortal Kombat: relembre os fatalities cl\u00e1ssicos da s\u00e9rie de luta &#124; Listas |publisher=TechTudo |date= |accessdate=2015-05-07}}</ref> Featuring her in their \"Girls of Gaming\" special in 2003, ''[[Play (US magazine)|play]]'' cited this Fatality as the aspect of Kitana that she is famous for.<ref>''Play magazine presents: girls of gaming'' #1.</ref> Her death kiss was ranked as the eighth-best of all ''Mortal Kombat'' Fatalities by both UGO in 2007 and IGN in 2010.<ref>[http://www.ugo.com/games/top-11-mortal-kombat-fatalities Top 11 Mortal Kombat Fatalities] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130401202148/http://www.ugo.com/games/top-11-mortal-kombat-fatalities |date=2013-04-01 }}, UGO.com, 2 January 2007.</ref><ref>Jack DeVries, [https://uk.ign.com/articles/2010/11/30/igns-unofficial-top-10-list-of-the-best-mortal-kombat-fatalities \"IGN's Unofficial Top 10 List of the Best Mortal Kombat Fatalities\"], IGN, November 30, 2010.</ref> In 2011, GameFront's Ben Richardson ranked it as the second best finishing move in the series for being \"just icing on the cake\" for ''MKI'''s combination of gore and [[dark comedy]], echoing Ed Boon's opinion.<ref name=br>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamefront.com/mortal-kombats-10-best-fatalities|title=Mortal Kombat's 10 Best Fatalities|first=Ben|last=Richardson|publisher=GameFront|date=April 20, 2011}}</ref> It was ranked as the sixth top Fatality in the series by WatchMojo.com in 2013,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://on.aol.com/video/top-10-mortal-kombat-fatalities-518035162 |title=Top 10 Mortal Kombat Fatalities|publisher=On.aol.com |date= |accessdate=2013-12-20}}</ref> as the 18th top ''Mortal Kombat'' finishing move by Kevin Wong of ''Complex'' that same year,<ref name=wong>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2013/10/best-mortal-kombat-finishing-moves-video-game-history/kitana |title=18. Exploding Kiss of Death\u2014The Best \"Mortal Kombat\" Finishing Moves in Video Game History |magazine=Complex |date=2013-10-01 |accessdate=2014-01-14}}</ref> and as the eighth-best Fatality by Robert Workman of Prima Games in 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.primagames.com/games/mortal-kombat/feature/top-50-mortal-kombat-fatalities-all-time-10-1 |title=The Top 50 Mortal Kombat Fatalities of All Time: 10-1 &#124; Feature |publisher=Primagames.com |date=2011-04-19 |accessdate=2014-05-13}}</ref> as well as included among the deadliest kisses in all of science fiction and fantasy by Gordon Jackson from io9 in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|author=gordonmjackson |url=http://io9.com/the-deadliest-kisses-in-all-of-science-fiction-and-fant-1746237456 |title=The Deadliest Kisses In All of Science Fiction and Fantasy |website=Io9.com |date= |accessdate=2016-01-01}}</ref> Javy Gwaltney of ''[[Paste Magazine]]'' put Kitana's kiss from ''MKII'' third on his 2015 list of \"the 15 most memorable Fatalities in ''Mortal Kombat''\", which also included Kitana cutting an opponent into pieces in ''MKX'', commenting it is \"of little surprise that Princess Kitana is a long-time ''Mortal Kombat'' fan favorite\" as her finishing moves \"are consistently fantastic.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Gwaltney |first=Javy |url=https://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2015/05/the-15-most-memorable-fatalities-in-mortal-kombat.html |title=The 15 Most Memorable Fatalities in Mortal Kombat :: Games :: Lists :: Paste |publisher=Pastemagazine.com |date= |accessdate=2015-07-01}}</ref> However, Kitana's kiss was also included on the list of the series' seven worst Fatalities by Dan Ryckert of ''[[Game Informer]]'' in 2010,<ref>Dan Ryckert, [http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2010/05/03/the-best-and-worst-mk-fatalities.aspx?PostPageIndex=2&PageIndex=4 Mortal Kombat's Best And Worst Fatalities], ''Game Informer'', May 03, 2010.</ref> and C.J. Smillie of Game Rant ranked it as the series' eighth-worst Fatality in 2011, criticizing it for not innovating enough over the years and stating that this \"unoriginality...really hurts Kitana's standing in the series.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamerant.com/worst-mortal-kombat-fatalities-cj-79624/all/1/|title=Top Ten Worst Mortal Kombat Fatalities|author=C.J. Smillie|date=April 19, 2011|publisher=Game Rant|accessdate=2011-12-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006073910/http://gamerant.com/worst-mortal-kombat-fatalities-cj-79624/all/1/|archive-date=October 6, 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> In another article, Smillie ranked Kitana's new \"Splitting Headache\" Fatality from ''MK2011'' placed as the eighth best finishing move in this game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamerant.com/best-fatalities-mortal-kombat-9-2011-cj-80814/all/1/|title=Top 10 Fatalities Of Mortal Kombat 9 (2011)|author=C.J. Smillie|date=April 19, 2011|publisher=Game Rant|accessdate=2011-12-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131003044903/http://gamerant.com/best-fatalities-mortal-kombat-9-2011-cj-80814/all/1/|archive-date=October 3, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Back in 1996, her rabbit Animality was also singled out as especially \"weak and poorly conceived\" in ''GamePro''<nowiki/>'s review of ''Ultimate Mortal Kombat 3''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=July 1996|title=Ultimate Mortal Kombat 3|url=https://archive.org/details/GamePro_Issue_094_Volume_08_Number_07_1996-07_IDG_Publishing_US/page/n67|journal=GamePro|publisher=IDG Publishing|volume=94|pages=67|via=}}</ref>\n\n====Other reception====\nIn various articles, often being tongue-in-cheek, Soren Bowie of Mania.com listed Kitana as one of ten \"psychotic video game chicks with too much baggage,\"<ref>Soren Bowie, [http://www.mania.com/top-10-hot-but-mostly-bothered-video-game-females_article_58486.html \"The Top 10 Hot But Mostly Bothered Video Game Females\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090205145840/http://www.mania.com/top-10-hot-but-mostly-bothered-video-game-females_article_58486.html |date=2009-02-05 }}, Mania.com, May 29, 2008.</ref> GameDaily featured her as one of ten \"babes who shouldn't meet your mom,\"<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20080626063618/http://www.gamedaily.com/articles/galleries/ten-babes-who-should-and-10-babes-who-shouldnt-meet-your-mom/?page=10 \"Ten Babes Who Should and 10 Babes Who Shouldn't Meet Your Mom\"], GameDaily, June 20, 2008.</ref> GamesRadar's Alan Bradley included her among \"gaming's most twisted royalty\" for having \"a thing for bloody decapitations via razor fan and for boys 9,000 years her junior,\"<ref>Alan Bradley, [https://www.gamesradar.com/gamings-most-twisted-royalty/ \"Gaming's most twisted royalty\"], GamesRadar, 2010-11-30.</ref> and [[Jim Sterling]] of [[Destructoid]] expressed his discomfort at Kitana's design in ''MK Vs. DCU'', implying her bulging crotch made her look like a transvestite.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.destructoid.com/why-penis-why-mk-vs-dc-s-kitana-looks-lumpy-98300.phtml|title=Why Penis Why?: MK vs. DC's Kitana looks ... lumpy|first=Jim|last=Sterling|website=Destructoid|date=August 5, 2008|accessdate=September 7, 2014}}</ref> Leah Jackson from MTV's The Feed instead paired her with Kung Lao instead of Liu Kang, as he \"would offer great balance to Princess Kitana's often hectic lifestyle\" of \"always going off getting killed, resurrected, put under spells, or whatever new kind of hell is cooked up for her.\"<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.g4tv.com/thefeed/blog/post/712244/the-royal-wedding-videogame-princess-edition/ |title=The Royal Wedding: Videogame Princess Edition |website=G4tv.com |date=2011-04-28 |accessdate=2016-01-01}}</ref> The character's outfits were parodied in Grey Carter's \"Critical Miss\" comic strip at ''[[The Escapist (magazine)|The Escapist]]'', where Kitana is forced to wear skimpy costumes and high heels by her stepfather.<ref>Grey Carter, [http://www.escapistmagazine.com/articles/view/comics/critical-miss/8836-Mortal-Kombat Critical Miss: Mortal Kombat], The Escapist, May 3, 2011.</ref>\n\n''GamePro'''s AJ Glasser called Kitana her favorite female ''Mortal Kombat'' character, but nevertheless criticized the character's pre-reboot repertoire of special moves.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=http://www.gamepro.com/article/previews/216385/pax-2010-mortal-kombat-preview-kitana/|title=PAX 2010: Mortal Kombat Preview (Kitana)|magazine=GamePro |author=Glasser, AJ |date=September 4, 2010|accessdate=September 4, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100909030826/http://www.gamepro.com/article/previews/216385/pax-2010-mortal-kombat-preview-kitana/|archivedate=2010-09-09}}</ref> Ben Kendrick of Game Rant included Kitana in his 2011 list of ten \"most awesome\" ''Mortal Kombat'' characters in the \"honorable mentions\" section, but added that \"apart from possessing one of the cooler weapons\" in the game, she \"lacks the entertaining/alluring oddity\" of Mileena.<ref>Ben Kendrick, [http://gamerant.com/top-10-mortal-kombat-characters-benk-78857/2/ \"10 Most Awesome Mortal Kombat Characters\"], Game Rant, April 18, 2011.</ref> GameFront's Richardson opined that, Kitana's \"most amusing\" kiss-killing aside, she has \"not [been] a very compelling character.\"<ref name=br/> Some were much more dismissive of the character altogether. For instance, ''Game Informer'' listed her among the palette swapped ninja characters not wanted by them in the future ''Mortal Kombat'' games in 2010,<ref>Dan Ryckert, [http://www.gameinformer.com/b/features/archive/2010/06/21/who-we-want-and-dont-want-in-the-new-mortal-kombat.aspx?PostPageIndex=2&PageIndex=4 Who We Want (And Don't Want) In The New Mortal Kombat], ''Game Informer'', June 21, 2010.</ref> and [[Kotaku]]'s Mike Fahey wrote that \"the whole alien ninja woman thing\" was not \"quite my cup of tea.\"<ref>Mike Fahey, [http://kotaku.com/5901432/let-mortal-kombat-vita-transform-you-into-a-woman-wearing-an-ill+fitting-ninja-costume Let Mortal Kombat Vita Transform You Into a Woman Wearing an Ill-Fitting Ninja Costume], Kotaku, April 12, 2012.</ref> Reacting to one fan request to not \"waste a character slot\" on Kitana in ''MKX'', Ed Boon himself commented: \"How can {{sic|any1}} hate on Kitana?\"<ref>{{cite tweet|user=noobde|author=Ed Boon|number=480006533363671041|date=20 June 2014|title=RT @eddyboyprime where the hell did all these Kitana fans come from, dont waste a character slot on her Ed! EB: How can any1 hate on Kitana?}}</ref>\n\nThe alternative versions of the character in other media have been variably received. At the time of the release, some film critics such as Laura Evenson of ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' or Eric D. Snider noted Talisa Soto's attractiveness in the role of Kitana but found her character otherwise uninteresting as compared to [[Robin Shou]]'s Liu Kang.<ref>{{cite news|author=Laura Evenson |url=http://www.sfgate.com/entertainment/article/Kombat-Just-for-Kicks-Game-s-fans-will-3026016.php |title=`Kombat' - Just for Kicks / Game's fans will like campy film version |newspaper=SFGate |date=1995-08-19 |accessdate=2013-12-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ericdsnider.com/movies/mortal-kombat/ |title=Movie Review - Mortal Kombat|first=Eric D.|last=Snider |publisher=www.ericdsnider.com |date=1995-08-18 |accessdate=2013-12-20}}</ref> Michael Saunders of ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' opined \"Soto never seems to do much more other than look exotic in the role,\"<ref>'Kombat' sequel is a bloodless 'Annihilation', ''The Tuscaloosa News'', November 26, 1997.</ref> which Ben Steelman of ''[[Star-News]]'' described as \"basically [[Princess Leia]] in black leotards,\"<ref>Ben Steelman, All 'Mortal Kombat' needs is a joystick at your seat, ''Star-News'', August 19, 1995.</ref> and Malcolm Johnson of the ''[[Hartford Courant]]'' described Kitana in ''Annihilation'' as wearing \"a knockout black leather costume [that] gives her the look of the world's sweetest dominatrix.\"<ref name=\"courant\">{{cite news|url=http://articles.courant.com/1997-11-22/features/9711220078_1_liu-kang-sonya-blades-lawrence-kasanoff|title=A Terrible but Amusing Action Movie|first=Malcolm|last=Johnson|newspaper=Hartford Courant|date=November 22, 1997|accessdate=September 8, 2014}}</ref> albeit Destructoid's Sterling included Kitana among the first film's \"more sensible makeovers\" comparing them to how ''[[X-Men]]'' comics characters were redesigned for the film adaptations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.destructoid.com/mortal-kombat-really-did-have-the-best-game-based-movie-199473.phtml|title=Mortal Kombat really did have the best game-based movie|first=Jim|last=Sterling|website=Destructoid|date=April 23, 2011|accessdate=September 7, 2014}}</ref> Dimas Sanfiorenzo of ''Complex'' ranked the animated Kitana in ''Defenders of the Realm'' as 18th on the list of \"hottest cartoon women of all time\" in 2011,<ref>Dimas Sanfiorenzo, [http://www.complex.com/pop-culture/2011/01/the-25-hottest-cartoon-women-of-all-time/princess-kitana \"The 25 Hottest Cartoon Women Of All Time\"], ''Complex'', January 28, 2011.</ref> while the feature film version of Kitana was ranked fourth on the list of \"hottest women in [[List of films based on video games|video game movies]]\" by Peter Rubin of ''Complex'', with a likeness score of 70%.<ref name=movies>Peter Rubin, [http://www.complex.com/video-games/2011/02/the-15-hottest-women-in-video-game-movies/kitana The 15 Hottest Women In Video Game Movies], ''Complex'', February 16, 2011.</ref> The ''Legacy'' episode \"Kitana & Mileena\" was nominated by the [[Writers Guild of America Award]] in the category \"Outstanding Achievement in Writing Derivative New Media\".<ref>Steve Pond at TheWrap, [https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/01/11/idUS59054142720120111 \"Mortal Kombat\" Scores in Writers Guild's New Media and Videogame Nominations], Reuters, January 11, 2012.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Commons category-inline}}\n*[[Ninja in popular culture]]\n\n==Notes== <!-- for side-notes and non-canonical game information that I didn't feel fit in the article's main body -->\n{{Reflist|group=\"note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Mortal Kombat characters}}\n\n[[Category:Action film characters]]\n[[Category:Adoptee characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Characters created by John Tobias]]\n[[Category:Emperor and empress characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Extraterrestrial characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Female characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional assassins in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional Baguazhang practitioners]]\n[[Category:Fictional bojutsuka]]\n[[Category:Fictional female assassins]]\n[[Category:Fictional female martial artists]]\n[[Category:Fictional female ninja]]\n[[Category:Fictional slaves in video games]]\n[[Category:Fictional tessenjutsuka]]\n[[Category:Fictional victims of kidnapping]]\n[[Category:Fictional Ying Zhao Pai practitioners]]\n[[Category:Mortal Kombat characters]]\n[[Category:Ninja characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Orphan characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Princess characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Twin characters in video games]]\n[[Category:Video game bosses]]\n[[Category:Video game antagonists]]\n[[Category:Video game characters in comics]]\n[[Category:Video game characters in film]]\n[[Category:Video game characters in 